<HEAD>Treasure Hunters Hope Sunken Ship Will Be 17th Century Galleon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A well-preserved ship believed to be a 17th century Spanish galleon loaded with gold has been found in 1,500 feet of water near the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Keys </LOCATION>, according to a salvage company. Much of the wooden vessel and its cargo appears to be intact because of the pressure and temperature of the water. `` It's worth a fortune in history.'' <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Stemm </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> businessman who hopes to recover the riches, told The <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petersburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> for an article published Wednesday. <PERSON> Stemm </PERSON> believes the wreck is the <ORGANIZATION> Nuestra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senora </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> la </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merced </ORGANIZATION>, a Spanish Colonial galleon believed to have vanished during the same hurricane 350 years ago that felled another galleon, the <LOCATION> Nuestra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Senora </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atocha </LOCATION>. The Atocha, laden with gold and silver, was found by treasure hunter <PERSON> Mel </PERSON> <PERSON> Fisher </PERSON> in 1985, about 50 miles north of <PERSON> Stemm </PERSON>'s discovery. If <PERSON> Stemm </PERSON>'s research proves correct, the wreck he discovered could hold a treasure worth millions. <PERSON> Stemm </PERSON>, 32, is co-owner of a deep-sea research company that discovered the sunken vessel in April. <ORGANIZATION> Seahawk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deep </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ocean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tampa </ORGANIZATION> plans to disclose the details of its remote-camera exploration of the ship on Wednesday. Archaeologist and treasure hunters are hoping photos prove it's the Merced, sunk in 1622. `` This is just like a time capsule because nothing's been touched,'' said <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bagley </PERSON>, a Seahawk director. By the end of the summer, the salvors aboard <PERSON> Stemm </PERSON>'s 85-foot research vessel Seahawk will begin a full-scale operation to retrieve the fragile artifacts and confirm the ship's identity. So far, they have discovered a ship's bell and a number of olive jars that could be filled with wine, food and other commodities. The project could take up to two years. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, a state archaeologist, said he has talked to the salvors about the importance of preserving the artifacts and other salvageable items from the wreck. `` Regardless of what vessel it is, archaeologically, it's an extremely significant site,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` If you consider the historic value, it's very great. The other side of that question is the monetary value.''
</TEXT>
