<SECOND>PM-Hunger Striker,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmate Protests Conviction with Lengthy Hunger Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY DAUBENMIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT CLEMENS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Acuna </PERSON> is starving himself to protest a life prison sentence, but he's on a well-worn road that state corrections officials say will end in court-ordered force feeding. `` I am innocent and I do n't eat,'' said <PERSON> Acuna </PERSON>, a Cuban immigrant who speaks broken English. <PERSON> Acuna </PERSON>, 37, of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, stopped eating _ except for water and sugared coffee _ March 3 after he was convicted of conspiracy and delivery of two pounds of cocaine. His sentence is life without parole. <PERSON> Acuna </PERSON> once carried 180 pounds on his 5-foot, 5-inch frame. As of Friday, he had lost 64 pounds. His body swims in his prison blues. His cheeks are sunken. `` I see the food like a chair, like a sofa. The hunger? When you have a reason to support your spirit and your mind, you do n't need anything more,'' he said in a telephone interview from the hospital at the State Prison of <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>. But a series of court rulings across the nation have upheld the power of prison officials to force feed inmates on long-term hunger strikes. Corrections experts say no record is kept of how many hunger strikes occur each year in American prisons, but they believe long ones are rare. Typically, courts decide that prison authorities' need to control their institutions outweighs prisoners' rights to privacy and control of their bodies, said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Koren </PERSON>, staff assistant for the National Prison Project of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. `` Obviously, they have an interest in controlling the institution and when a prisoner does something like this, he is embarrassing the heck out of them,'' he said. Department of Corrections officials label <PERSON> Acuna </PERSON>'s hunger strike a publicity stunt, and have doctors check him each day. The department will go to court to get the authority to force feed him if his condition worsens, said <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lalonde </PERSON>, deputy director of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION>, adding `` that could be today. That could be tomorrow.'' <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> officials seek such authority about 10 times a year in order to safeguard the health of inmates who refuse food or medical care, said <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> DeWitt </PERSON>, spokesman for Attorney General <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON>. <PERSON> Acuna </PERSON>'s lawyers say his determination poses an ethical dilemma. `` This is the stuff ` <LOCATION> L.A. </LOCATION> Law' is written about. What do you do when your client wants to die?'' asked <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuhard </PERSON>, director of the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Appellate Defender's office, which will handle the appeal of <PERSON> Acuna </PERSON>'s drug convictions. `` I told him if he dies from not eating, even if he is innocent, his appeal will be stopped right then,'' said <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Girard </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> Prison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. In a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION> case, inmate <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Calk </PERSON> decided to starve himself to death rather than serve a 180-year sentence. <PERSON> Arpy </PERSON> <PERSON> Saunders </PERSON>, <PERSON> Calk </PERSON>'s lawyer, said the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> allowed authorities to force-feed <PERSON> Calk </PERSON> to keep him alive so that he could face another charge pending in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` It was n't up to him to determine how long he should serve,'' said <PERSON> Saunders </PERSON>, summarizing the court's ruling. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>, sentenced to 20 years to life for the murder of former Beatle <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lennon </PERSON>, staged a hunger strike to call attention to starving children. But the appellate division of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decided prison security needs outweighed <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>'s claim that the right to privacy includes a right to refuse to eat. One exception to that philosophy came in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, where inmate <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Prevatte </PERSON> won a lawsuit to prevent authorities from force-feeding him, but eventually ended his hunger strike, aimed at winning transfer to another prison system, said <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Siler </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> found force-feeding was too great an invasion of an inmate's right to privacy, saying the state `` has no right to destroy a person's will by frustrating his attempt to die if necessary to make a point.''
