<FIRST>r i PM-FearofFlying     06-27 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fear of Flying,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former European Parliament Member Fined for Plane Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fear of flying has cost a former British member of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> $ 1,240, the fine imposed by a court because he refused to fasten his airplane seat belt. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Cottrell </PERSON>, 45, was arrested at <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> on May 24 after arriving from <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> on a <ORGANIZATION> Lufthansa </ORGANIZATION> flight. An airline spokeswoman said at the time that <PERSON> Cottrell </PERSON> had refused to fasten his seat belt as the flight approached <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and attempted to continue the argument in the cockpit with the captain. <PERSON> Cottrell </PERSON>, a Conservative, was fined Monday after pleading guilty to acting in a manner likely to endanger an aircraft or the people aboard. At the magistrate's court hearing, the defense said <PERSON> Cottrell </PERSON>'s fear of flying was the reason he refused to fasten his seat belt <PERSON> Cottrell </PERSON> went to the cockpit door and told the pilot, `` I am a member of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>,'' after he was told international regulations required all passengers to wear seat belts, the court was told. Prosecutor <PERSON> Neville </PERSON> <PERSON> Casselmann </PERSON> said <PERSON> Cottrell </PERSON> remained at the cockpit until the pilot shouted: `` Out _ we are landing.'' He returned to his seat about two minutes before the landing. Defense attorney <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Darby </PERSON> said his client `` for some considerable time had a large-scale phobia of flying. It arose out of an incident 15 years ago when he was a passenger in a light aircraft forced to make an emergency landing. He was badly shaken up by it.'' He added that his client `` always sits near the emergency exits and never fastens his seat belt.'' In this month's European <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> elections, <PERSON> Cottrell </PERSON> lost the <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION>, western <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, seat he had held for 10 years.
