<HEAD>Harvard, Union Reach Tentative Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and its clerical workers' union said Monday they have reached tentative agreement on their first contract, culminating 17 years of labor organizing and four months of negotiations. The union's chief negotiator, <PERSON> Kristine </PERSON> <PERSON> Rondeau </PERSON>, said the pact would provide pay raises averaging 32 percent over the next three years. `` It's the prettiest contract you've ever seen,'' said <PERSON> Rondeau </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> laboratory assistant who led the campaign that succeeded last year in organizing the 3,500 workers over strenuous opposition from the university. `` It's got great economics and cooperative labor-management relations, and it addresses the concerns of working women,'' she said. Former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of Labor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunlop </PERSON>, a professor of economics at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, led the university's bargaining team. The negotiators, who had been meeting since February, said they reached agreement in principle late Sunday night. The <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clerical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> is scheduled to hold a ratification vote Thursday. The tentative contract provides several new benefits, including a $ 50,000 annual scholarship fund for child care and eight weeks of paid maternity leave. It also gives the workers free use of the university's athletic facilities, increases their dental and pension benefits and raises the university's contribution to their health insurance premiums to 85 percent from 70 percent. The union, which is affiliated with the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION>, represents secretaries, library aides, laboratory personnel and mailroom workers throughout the university. The effort to form a union among the clerical workers, 83 percent of whom are women, began in 1972. It culminated in a May 17, 1988, vote that the labor organizers won by 44 votes, or less than 2 percent of the total cast in the 1,530-1 ,486 decision Harvard President <PERSON> Derek </PERSON> <PERSON> Bok </PERSON>, a former law professor whose academic writings have been supportive of labor unions, opposed the union's formation. The university challenged the vote before the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> but lost. <PERSON> Bok </PERSON> said Monday the university will work with the union to complete and sign the formal contract. `` We look forwad with increasing confidence to a positive relationshp between <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> and the union,'' he said. <PERSON> Rondeau </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dunlop </PERSON> tried to foster an atmosphere of cooperation and goodwill toward the union in the aftermath of the bitter organizing battle. `` I think he did everything that he could to change the way the university and the union related to each other, and I think he did a good job at that,'' she said. <PERSON> Dunlop </PERSON> was traveling to <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Monday evening and could not be reached for comment.
