<HEAD>Koochi Nomads Embody The Spirit Of Afghanistan ^An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> TANGIYE </LOCATION> <LOCATION> POL-I-CHARKI </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ Bearded, turbaned men slowly guide their camels, sheep and goats down the mountains and carry lambs on their shoulders along the rugged path. Women in colorful traditional dress and small children run beside the flock to keep the bleating animals from straying. They travel along the potholed road past the artillery guns and tanks and through this military checkpoint, undisturbed by the soldiers. `` We are free people,'' <PERSON> Habibullah </PERSON> said as he unloaded sacks of goods from his kneeling camel. `` We are the true spirit of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Or maybe we're what <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> used to be.'' <PERSON> Habibullah </PERSON> and the other 15 members of his clan are among the estimated 2 million Koochi nomads who wander between winter and summer pastures, pitching their hide tents in fields, building fires and turning their sheep to graze. The Koochis, which means wanderer in the <LOCATION> Pashto </LOCATION> language, have traveled the rugged hills and valleys of Afghanstian for thousands of years. They are ethnic Pathans, like most people in eastern <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. But unlike their brothers, they never settled down. Most still divide their time between the warm lowlands around <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, and the hilly fields of northern and central <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The 11-year-old civil war has made the journey more difficult for the Koochis. But it has n't stopped them. <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, the capital, is a common stopping point for the <LOCATION> Koochis </LOCATION>, and their camel trains are as much a part of the urban landscape as the old bazaars, the military outposts and high-rise apartment buildings. They halt in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> at least once a year to sell camels, sheep and goats at the meat market. `` The <LOCATION> Koochi </LOCATION> people are an important part of our homeland, an important part of our tradition. We respect them,'' said <PERSON> Sulaiman </PERSON> <PERSON> Laeq </PERSON>, the minister of clans and a Politburo member. The government has tried to provide them with education, health and the benefits of progress, such as helping them purchase trucks and organize a transport union. But the Koochis have made it clear they do n't want to enter the modern world, especially if it means owing alligence to the ruling <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Afghanistan </ORGANIZATION> or any other government. In the early days of the 1978 Marxist revolution that touched off the civil war, efforts were made to force the <LOCATION> Koochis </LOCATION> to stop wandering and settle in the north. The move backfired, said the 37-year-old <PERSON> Habibullah </PERSON>. Some of the <PERSON> Koochis </PERSON> took up guns and joined the Moslem guerrillas in the battle against the Soviet-backed government troops. `` Some are still fighting, but most have returned,'' <PERSON> Habibullah </PERSON> said through a translator. Laeq and other party officials speak of the mistakes the government made while trying to bring progress to the <LOCATION> Koochis </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Koochi </PERSON> men had never been asked to serve in the Afghan armed forces, but that tradition was reversed when the Marxists seized power 11 years ago in a bloody coup. By 1985, the government had modified its policy, formally exempting the <LOCATION> Koochi </LOCATION> men from government military service. But the war has not been easy for the Koochis. They often step on land mines planted by the armed forces and by the Soviets during their nine-year intervention. And their travels frequently take them into battle zones near <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, an eastern city under rebel siege since early March. `` This war has been very bad for our people,'' says another <LOCATION> Koochi </LOCATION> leader, <PERSON> Azizullah </PERSON>. `` The bombs, and rockets and land mines have killed so many of our people.'' Occasionally, he says, the rebels demand money to allow them to pass through guerrilla-controlled territory. Often the roads are neither open nor safe, forcing the <LOCATION> Koochis </LOCATION> to travel through the mountains and turning an easy one-day journey into a dangerous, two-week affair. `` We are our own people. We do n't want to be on either side,'' says <PERSON> Azizullah </PERSON>. `` We do n't want anyone else's war.''
</TEXT>
