<FIRST>r i PM-China-ForeignPress Bjt   06-27 0836</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Foreign Press, Bjt,0867</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Press Uses Imaginative Tactics to Report Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Covering the news in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> under the growing obstacles created by martial law requires more in the way of imaginative tactics by foreign journalists than derring-do. Reporting on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s political crisis has become increasingly difficult as soldiers and police strictly enforce restrictions on the press. Newsgathering is basically banned under martial law, except for the infrequent government-orchestrated peasant rally or news conference. But virtually all reporters in the capital and other <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> cities ignore the regulations, coming up with their own ways of getting around martial law. `` The most effective trick these days is to act like a dumb tourist,'' says an Asian photojournalist. `` Wear bright clothes and shorts, and do n't hide your camera.'' If stopped by security personnel, he says, `` the best defense is to go on the offense. Ask them some questions. It's better than trying to run away.'' Martial law was imposed May 20 in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> in a move to quell the student-led democracy movement that was finally crushed June 4 when soldiers killed hundreds of unarmed civilians in the capital. Under the vaguely worded decree, foreigners are prohibited from entering or taking pictures at schools, factories or `` organizations''. Television networks face the greatest difficulties. Their equipment makes them easy to spot. `` For television, we do n't have a story unless we have a picture that can convey the information,'' says a CBS News official. `` We get chased away all the time. We're very frustrated at not being able to shoot pictures.'' Coverage has been reduced to relying on government-controlled TV news. `` A great deal of what we're doing is recording their material and reworking it,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> official. `` We're very much at their mercy.'' Foreign television networks can no longer send segments through state-run <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> via satellite. They must now somehow get their videotapes to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` We smuggled out our tapes, did the double shuffle with the cassettes and that sort,'' said <PERSON> Vernon </PERSON> <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>, a correspondent for <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> whose videotape was `` confiscated'' by police after he filmed on a university campus in <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION>, central <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` Our piece, which would have greatly upset them, was aired all over the <LOCATION> U.K. </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kingdom </LOCATION> -RRB-.'' <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> was expelled from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for the incident. Still photographers have an easier time. One wrapped his camera in a jacket and put the bundle in his bicycle basket, shooting frames as he passed soldiers guarding intersections. Another put aside his complex single-lens reflex camera and instead went out with the automatic-focus variety so all he had to do was point and push. Most photographers have resorted to taking pictures from cars, some with darkened windows, as they zip past soldiers on patrol or troops checking identification. One cameraman from a European photo agency took a dramatic shot through the back window of a taxi of a man in handcuffs being led away by soldiers. `` One guy saw me, and I just hit my driver on the back and said, ` Let's get out of here!,''' he said. Print journalists face more subtle difficulties. With most Chinese frightened into silence by widespread arrests, including the nationally publicized arrest of a man who talked to an American television crew, reporters' sources are drying up. `` I've simply stopped telephoning people,'' said one <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> reporter, noting that he and most colleagues assume their phones are tapped. `` I think of my Chinese contacts first and foremost as friends and I've stopped making any attempt to contact them.'' Other journalists discover that acquaintances refuse to meet them. A German reporter was turned away when he showed up at the doorsteps of some Chinese friends. He says now he does not even take notes on the streets, preferring to keep his eyes open and later write down what he saw. The few who do make appointments do so with great caution, calling from public telephones, instructing friends not to say their names in phone conversations, making appointments by prearranged code and meeting sources furtively in discrete locations. `` I only move around at night,'' said a Japanese reporter. `` Even though it's easier for me to blend into a crowd than Westerners, I still stand out.'' He says while many people who have helped him have gone underground, he has n't stopped seeing people because `` Chinese have information you ca n't get otherwise.'' He, too, says meetings are much harder to arrange. `` You ca n't meet people in hotels _ they have secret cameras everywhere,'' referring to footage taken by a hidden camera of a student leader feasting at the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Hotel Now he finds the only place he can interview people is in his car _ during the day, when soldiers are n't checking vehicles for fugitives. `` The greatest danger in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> now is that the people have lost their voice,'' he said. `` The reformists and intellectuals are all gone. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> have lost its good-heartedness.''
