<HEAD>Bush Welcomes Former Democrats to the GOP</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Ceremony for Hawke begins 10 a.m. EDT; will be led</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, welcoming five dozen state and local officials into the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>, says the political converts are just part of the `` droves of voters'' being shut out by a left-leaning <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who often extols the virtues of bipartisanship in dealing with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, reached back for some campaign-style rhetoric Monday at the White House event where the Republicans paraded the party-switchers. `` The Democratic party is leaving droves of voters behind as it moves over onto the more liberal side, the left side of the political equation. And now many of those stranded voters have made a move on their own to the Republican party, our party of family, faith and the future,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had a different sort of White House ceremony on tap today with plans to greet Australian Prime Minister <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawke </PERSON> with full military honors followed by a private meeting and, in the evening, a state dinner. The emphasis was on politics Monday when the ex-Democrats trekked through the Oval Office to pose for official pictures with the president and hear their praises sung in the Rose Garden by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, GOP Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> and Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> <PERSON> of </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, who made his own switch to the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> in February. `` You're tough,'' <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> told the state representatives, judges, sheriffs, mayors and other officials. At home, he said, `` you're being accused of being a traitor, turncoat, accused of betraying the voters by leaving the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> praised their political courage and promised to stand `` shoulder to shoulder'' with them as they seek re-election as Republicans. `` The switch is on to the party in sync with the American principles. The switch is on to the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>,'' said the president. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, employing the rhetoric he successfully used to hammer Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in the presidential campaign, said Republicans were moving `` in the right direction.'' The Democrats are `` on the move, too, to the left and out of the mainstream,'' he said. <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON>, embroiled in controversy recently over a <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> attack on new House Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, called the event `` absolutely the proudest single moment I've had since taking office.'' He said the new Republicans were just part of 118 elected officials who have switched to the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> `` since my chairmanship began'' in January. `` And I know of no single example of a Republican party official ... who has switched the other way,'' he said. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Evers </PERSON>, outgoing mayor of <LOCATION> Fayette </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, and brother of slain civil rights leader <PERSON> Medgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Evers </PERSON>, said he switched parties because `` I do n't like to be with losers. The <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is a loser.'' <PERSON> Evers </PERSON> added that he did n't want to see an all-white <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. He said he will try to encourage black voters in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> to register Republican because blacks are better off with representation in both parties. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Allenhurst </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, dentist and environmental activist running for the state assembly, was one of only a few politicians from north of the Mason-Dixon line identified among the new Republicans. He said he changed parties because of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s promise to `` make ending ocean pollution a priority in his administration.''
