<HEAD>Tanker Accidents Raise Political Heat on Oil Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> WASHINGTON </LOCATION> _ The latest oil shipping accidents in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> waters are raising the likelihood <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will widen restrictions on drilling in promising areas off the shores of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and other states, oil industry analysts and lawmakers say. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is to consider Wednesday a bill containing tough limits on oil development in the <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> area of the southern <LOCATION> Bering </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> and in federally controlled waters off <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Keys </LOCATION>. Rep. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Pallone </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, predicted Monday the legislation will pass the full <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> this session, in part because of publicity about oil spills over the weekend in the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>'s ship channel and near <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION> `` They just point out how delicate the near-shore environment is,'' <PERSON> Pallone </PERSON> said in an interview. He wrote letters to several major oil companies earlier this month asking them not to bid for federal lease sales off the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> coast. Presidential press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said Monday the latest spills show the `` pervasiveness of the problem'' but do n't require new steps by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> such as initiatives to limit oil exploration The latest spills were a significant blow to the oil industry, which is still reeling from the devastating Exxon Valdez oil spill March 24 in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. That accident, the worst spill in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history, almost immediately killed chances for congressional approval of legislation to open the <ORGANIZATION> Arctic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Refuge </ORGANIZATION>, on <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s North Slope, to oil and natural gas exploration. A further consequence of the recent tanker accidents _ and public criticism of the industry's cleanup response _ may be a new ban on exploration in <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, a rich fishing area <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s state government says is more vulnerable to spill damage than Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. `` They'll stop <LOCATION> Bristol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>'' exploration, <PERSON> Dillard </PERSON> <PERSON> Spriggs </PERSON>, president of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> consulting company <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Analysis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday. `` It's going to be hard to explore very much in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'' until the industry improves its public image. Although most of the Capitol Hill focus on offshore oil exploration has been limited to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, movements to ban or slow down drilling have emerged in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. The oil industry, long aware of political pressures to limit offshore drilling, until recently sought to rely on its past safety record and assertions that less domestic drilling will mean more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> reliance on foreign suppliers. But since the Valdez accident exposed the industry's inability to handle large-scale spills, oil companies have tried to take the offensive by promising to devote more money, personnel and equipment to responding to major accidents. The latest spills came just days after a special task force of oil executives announced plans to spend $ 250 million over five years to create a nationwide network of cleanup equipment and workers to handle a major spill on any coastal waterway. The cleanup system is not expected to be working until next summer. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, representing the major oil companies, gave a muted response to the weekend spills. It said although its proposed regional response centers will be designed to handle worse disasters, the centers could have been called into action by the government if they had been in place. The industry counters anti-drilling arguments by noting that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dependence on foreign oil has risen sharply in recent years. Imported oil makes up about 45 percent of total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> supplies and the foreign share is expected to grow unless major oil fields are discovered on federal land. The industry and the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration say such reliance on foreign suppliers undermines <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> energy security and means more environmental risk from foreign tanker traffic. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is awaiting the recommendations of a task force he assembled in March to review potential environment damage from oil and natural gas drilling in federal waters off northern and southern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and the southern Gulf coast of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. The group is to report by Jan. 1.
