<HEAD>Problems May be Everywhere in HUD, Investigators Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Abuse and mismanagement may be everywhere in the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, say investigators who confess they do n't know where their probe will be headed next. `` We have made the assumption that there is a problem within every unit within <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>, and until we learn that there is n't, we're going to assume that there is,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Shays </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Conn </LOCATION>., a member of the congressional panel investigating the So far, the investigations have roamed from one unrelated program to the next and have been shotgunned from one part of the nation to another. A sampling from around the country: _ In <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> says his office is investigating allegations that a suspended <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> accountant embezzled some $ 1 million in housing funds _ In <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>, auditors are trying to account for $ 176,965 arising from 11 property sales _ In <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, a pair of real estate brokers are awaiting trial on charges of defrauding <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> of more than $ 900,000 _ In <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON>'s office has filed a civil suit against two <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> men the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says kept proceeds from <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> real estate closings The lawsuit, which contends <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 840,000 in payments and $ 860,000 in interest, seeks $ 7.5 million in damages. _ In the <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> suburbs of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, a private escrow agent has confessed to stealing more than $ 5 million from <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> Her role was to help the department close on sales of repossessed homes by signing papers and accepting the buyers' money for the property. <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrell </PERSON>, nicknamed `` <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> HUD'' because she gave some of the stolen money to the poor, told investigators her operation was simple: She just did n't give the government its money. On Monday, Ms. <PERSON> Harrell </PERSON> turned over her house to the department to cover part of the thefts. Ms. <PERSON> Harrell </PERSON> and unidentified agents in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> became the first agents that <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> will bar from future government contracts, the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported today, quoting <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Keating </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> general counsel-designate. Investigations involve 11 other private escrow agents around the country, and as much as $ 20 million of <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> funds may have been taken this way, according to <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, the department's inspector general. On another front, revealed just this week, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> has moved to halt losses from a loan program where some $ 650 million in mortgages are in default. The department moved swiftly to suspend three mortgage companies indefinitely, put three others on six-month probations and review the operations of still three more. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials say a certain amount of fraud is to be expected in a $ 20 billion government agency involved chiefly in making loans and giving away money to help people get shelter and aid the nation's