<HEAD>Drug Czar Defends Staff's Experience, Pace of Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drug czar <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> rejects criticism that he has hired people inexperienced with drug issues, saying his assistants understand the problem and what they do n't know, he finds out from his `` kitchen cabinet.'' `` There's plenty of experience,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said in an interview. `` There is n't anybody who knows all of it. All the people here know various pieces. We call on our colleagues in the government all the time, certainly on the Hill too.'' He can call on other experts to fill in some of the gaps, said <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, director of the Office of National Drug Control Policy. `` Calling in the experts is fine,'' he said. `` You do n't have to have everybody on staff. I've been given a fairly small staff and I have to make it travel a long way.'' Rep. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> on <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Narcotics </ORGANIZATION>, and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s chief narcotics officer said in interviews that <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> will have difficulty drawing up a national drug strategy, due in September, with his current staff The comments echoed criticisms against <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> by some federal officials, who spoke only on condition of anonymity. `` He's not going to be able to draw up a comprehensive strategy ... and prevent turf wars and figure out how to minimize duplication without having people who have worked in the agencies and know how to do that,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. `` <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> himself, without any real drug experience, has surrounded himself with people who do n't have any real drug experience, and, without that, they're going to be operating in a vacuum,'' he said. <PERSON> Sterling </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s special narcotics prosecutor, said, `` There is no one that I know of with any real law enforcement experience on his team.'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> has asked him to join his `` kitchen cabinet'' of unofficial advisers and he'll probably do so. `` I told him that I want him to succeed. If he fails, we all fail,'' said <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>'s chief of staff, defended the office's experience, saying more than half of its 60 workers have been sent there from `` every major federal agency involved in anti-drug efforts. Some three dozen federal agencies, including the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and the departments of Education and <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, are part of the war against illegal drugs. Some of the officials criticizing <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> come from agencies that opposed <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' creation of his office, which is charged with scrutinizing their budgets and priorities as it develops a national strategy. That oversight role, as well as traditional rivalry between agencies, may be responsible for some of the complaints, <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> said in an interview. `` Frankly, I am suspicious of some of the offers for help, because those take the form of a desire to write the strategy for us from people in particular agencies, on the <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> and elsewhere,'' <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> said. `` We want competent staff help, but we do not want someone to do our job for us.'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> also has generated criticism by deciding not to fill many permanent positions until his top two deputies are in place, depending for now on temporary staffers detailed from other agencies. His candidates for the deputy slots _ <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Marshals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> for the supply reduction job and Dr. <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleber </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> for the demand reduction job _ have not yet been nominated by the White House. <PERSON> Kleber </PERSON> is already on the payroll as a consultant. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said he has urged the White House to act on the nominations and he presumed the need for thorough background checks was causing the delay. But he added that he consults with both men regularly and the empty posts will not hinder preparation of an anti-drug strategy.
