<SECOND>PM-Splitting Venice,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vote to Split Venice In Two Fails</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VENICE, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Venetians have decided to stay together, defeating a referendum that called for divorcing the romantic lagoon city from a dependent, blue-collar suburb on the mainland. The referendum, with balloting on Sunday and Monday, was pressed for by officials in <PERSON> Mestre </PERSON>, a community that is administratively part of the city across the causeway but has little in common with the fabled place of singing gondoliers and smelly canals. <PERSON> Mestre </PERSON> politicians say the growing community's needs are different from those of aging, tourist-choked <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> and that <PERSON> Mestre </PERSON>'s identity is overwhelmed by <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>'s fame. While citizens of <PERSON> Mestre </PERSON> outnumber the citizens of historic <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>, 3-1, the measure nevertheless went down to defeat, 58 percent against separation, 42 percent in favor. Lacking affordable housing, young Venetians have been steadily moving out of the lagoon city to <PERSON> Mestre </PERSON>. In 1951, historic <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION> had 175,000 people while <PERSON> Mestre </PERSON> had about 50,000. In 1987, <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>'s population stood at 83,000 while <PERSON> Mestre </PERSON> has 250,000. With souvenir stores far outnumbering butcher and grocery shops, remaining Venetians depend greatly on <PERSON> Mestre </PERSON> for shopping. Ten years ago, a group of influential Venetians lobbied for a similar referendum. That proposal was defeated with more than 72 percent of the voters opposed to separation.
