<HEAD>Bush Affirms Need For Contacts With Chinese</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 17 grafs new with Bush news kfc, picking up 2nd graf pvs,
``In Asia, etc.; edits pvs to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said today he would keep trying to get in touch with the leaders of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> but acknowledged he had not been able to make contact in the last few weeks. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, at a White House news conference, said he had still not received a telephone call from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> despite his efforts to discuss the recent turmoil in the world's most populous nation. But <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said there have been `` some exchange of views'' at a lower level, And he stressed that the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> ambassador here, <PERSON> Han </PERSON> <PERSON> Xu </PERSON>, has had easy access to senior <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> first disclosed his inability to make contact at a news conference last week. He appealed publicly for a show of clemency, but executions proceeded. In his remarks, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was mildly critical of moves by the Chinese to suspend <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> visits to the country. `` That's too bad,'' he said, `` One of the things that moved reform is contacts with Americans. I do n't want to see those contacts cut off.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> again avoided any heavy denunciation of the arrests and executions in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` I reiterate my desire not to do damage to the people themselves.'' He said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> contacts with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> had promoted economic reform in the country. `` Someday we will move the process of political reform forward,'' he said. In the meantime, he said 30,000 Chinese now studying here will be `` going back there with a sense of what democracy and freedom is all about.'' He said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ties had helped <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> move out of a period of cultural isolation and that `` this relationship is important.'' Repeatedly, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said good relations with <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> are in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest. But he did not respond to two questions asking him to give specific examples. `` At this moment,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` it's impossible to have normal relations for very obvious reasons. But I am going to do my level best to find a way to see improvement there.'' And yet, the president said he could not `` dictate'' to the Chinese who should be leading the country. Since Army troops fired on students June 3-4 in Tiananmen Square the leadership of the government and the Communist party has been revised to remove leaders who showed some sympathy for democratic reform movements. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who headed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> liaison office in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and claims expertise in <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> affairs, said he could not have predicted the recent turn of events. But, he said, `` I guess the lesson is to go forward as best you can'' and `` to hold high the banner of values you believe in.'' Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, in a speech Monday night in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, was optimistic about long-term prospects for democracy. `` In <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, as in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, a new order is taking shape,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said in a speech summarizing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> Administration policy on <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. `` While the rites of passage will be painful _ <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> proves that _ it is an order full of promise and hope.'' `` We and some other nations have suspended business as usual,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` But we and the rest of the world must not let our revulsion at this repression blind us to pressure for reform.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> spoke for 25 minutes before 1,000 guests at a black-tie dinner of the <ORGANIZATION> Asia <