<HEAD>Bush Hails Progress in US-Soviet Ties; Experts Urge Push For START
Treaty</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 11 grafs new with Bush comments today; picking up 4th graf
pvs, bgng, ``But it....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JON KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> knows `` we want to move forward'' on a nuclear weapons reduction treaty and applauded <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> for visiting <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The president spoke to reporters a day after five former secretaries of state and defense urged the administration to push for the treaty but warned that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> does not know enough about <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> intentions `` to justify extraordinary political or economic concessions.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he had no timetable for a first summit meeting with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> but said such a meeting did not need to wait for a major treaty agreement between the superpowers. `` I do n't think it should be something to sign, but I'd like to think that the governing criterion would be that the world would see the meeting as successful, something good coming out of it,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, speaking in general terms about arms negotiations with the Soviets, said `` they know we want to move forward with START,'' an acronym for Strategic Arms Reduction Talks. `` I feel comfortable,'' about the pace of improvements in U.S-Soviet ties, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, adding that a number of medical and cultural exchanges had helped improve the relationship. `` We're coming closer on some of these broad, broad-scale objectives,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` All I want to say is I think the relationship is going in the right general direction albeit we have tremendous differences with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> still.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> applauded <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s recent visits to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and said he did not expect the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> `` to be uptight'' about his upcoming visit to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact ally of the Soviets. `` Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> goes to <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and he is well received; I will go to <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and I will be well received,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. The report released Monday and signed by the five secretaries and six other ex-officials also counseled <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to show restraint on developing space-based defenses. It concluded that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is more inclined than any of his predecessors to reach accords with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that further Western interests. But it added that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> knowledge of current and future <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> policy was `` too problematical to justify extraordinary political or economic concessions which we would otherwise not consider.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON>, secretary of defense in the <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> administration, criticized the Soviet leader for agreeing last week to resume arms aid to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. He said it showed <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is still seeking `` marginal advantage'' over the West and in that respect `` failing the test.'' Still, the report urged the administration to push hard to complete the treaty to reduce long-range bombers, missiles and submarines by 30 to 50 percent. After a seven-month recess, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration resumed negotiations last week in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. At the same time, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies are negotiating with the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> to reduce troops, tanks, artillery and other non-nuclear armories in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The report said completion of a strategic arms reduction treaty `` will make it easier for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its allies to obtain large and asymmetrical reductions in conventional arms, and should not wait on success in the latter.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> already has made `` especially significant'' commitments to cut more men and arms than the West and to shift the role of Soviet troops toward defense, the report said. `` I do worry,'' said <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, who was secretary of defense in the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration, `` if START is pushed to the back burner it will not get done at all. That would be a big mistake.'' <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, who held a joint news conference, were joined in the report by former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Laird </PERSON> and former Secretaries of State <PERSON> Cyrus </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vance </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Muskie </PERSON>. The other ex-officials who issued the report were <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Abshire </PERSON>, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Blumenthal </PERSON>, <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON>. On space-based defenses, they said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should be willing to recommit itself for 10 years to the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty and discuss with the Soviets what kind of tests for a space-based defense are permitted. This could have the effect of constraining the program undertaken by former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to develop a shield against Soviet ballistic missiles combining sophisticated technology and nuclear weapons in space. However, the report also suggested the 1972 treaty could be amended or a new one concluded with the Soviets through negotiations.
