<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Ruling That CBS Lost Trademark for Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today let stand a ruling that <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> no longer enjoys trademark protection for the `` Amos ` N' Andy'' radio and television shows The justices, without comment, refused to review a federal appeals court ruling that <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> abandoned the trademarks when, under pressure from civil rights groups, it suspended commercial use of the shows. The asserted trademarks were challenged by <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON>, who wants to produce a musical play based on the `` Amos ` N' Andy'' shows and their characters. The case now returns to a federal judge in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, who is to rule on other aspects of the dispute. Today's high court action does not remove all legal hurdles confronting <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON>. The characters of <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> were created in 1928 by <PERSON> Freeman </PERSON> <PERSON> Gosden </PERSON> and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Correll </PERSON>, who wrote and produced the `` Amos ` N' Andy'' radio program, one of the nation's most popular. <PERSON> Gosden </PERSON> and <PERSON> Correll </PERSON> were white, but <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> and <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> and all other characters portrayed on the program were black. <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> bought all rights to the show and its creations in 1948, and broadcast it until 1955. In 1951, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> began broadcasting an `` Amos ` N' Andy'' television show using black actors. The television series also attained great popularity, and a generation of TV viewers came to know <PERSON> George </PERSON> `` Kingfish'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>; his wife, <PERSON> Sapphire </PERSON>; lawyer <PERSON> Algonquin </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Calhoun </PERSON> and the Mystic Knights of the Sea Lodge. The television show was aired on <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> affiliate stations until 1953. It continued in reruns and non-network syndication until 1966, when <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> responded to criticism that the show presented a demeaning portrayal of blacks. <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON> in 1981 asked CBS for permission to produce a play based on a script called `` Amos ` N' Andy Go To the Movies.'' The play's proposed title later was changed to `` Amos ` N' Andy In <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>,'' and finally to `` Fresh Air Taxi.'' <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> refused permission, and <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON> sued in 1984. The suit alleged that <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> had no trademark or other exclusive rights in the material contained in the first 20 years of <ORGANIZATION> Amos </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> ` </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> N </ORGANIZATION>' Andy radio shows <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goettel </PERSON> ruled for <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> on the trademark issue. He said the network offered a reasonable explanation for its decision to keep the programs off the air and asserted its intention to resume use at some indefinite future date. But the 2nd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last Feb. 6 reversed that ruling. The appeals court said the trial judge misinterpeted the federal trademark law's handling of abandonment. `` More likely, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> wanted a mark to be deemed abandoned once use has been discontinued with an intent not to resume within the reasonably foreseeable future,'' the appeals court said. In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> said other appeals courts have ruled that `` an outside cause for suspension of use of a trademark precludes abandonment.'' The case is <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Silverman </PERSON>, 88-1804.
