<HEAD>Recator Accident May Have Contaminated Soviet Submarine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG MELLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A leak in the nuclear power system of a Soviet submarine probably contaminated the vessel but not the environment, a Norwegian expert said today. The submarine, built in the 1960s, billowed smoke and steam when its reactor's cooling system broke down Monday, 70 miles from the coast of northern <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. Soviet officials say there was no radiation leak. They say the reactor was shut down and no one was injured. But <PERSON> Knut </PERSON> <PERSON> Gussgard </PERSON>, acting chairman of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Peacetime Nuclear Accidents, said pieced-together details of the accident aboard the Echo-II Class submarine show a reactor cooling circuit most likely leaked radioactive water and steam into the vessel. Gussgard, from the Norwegian <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION>, said by telephone that too little information is available to judge the effect of such radiation on the crew. Just before Monday's accident, submarine Capt. <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ovisjinnkov </PERSON> was quoted as telling the Soviet publication <LOCATION> Smena </LOCATION> that <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear submarine crews are poorly trained, know little about procedures and can handle fewer than half the situations they should master. It was the second Soviet submarine accident in three months. On April 7, an advanced Mike Class nuclear submarine sank 207 miles away in the <LOCATION> Norwegian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. Forty-two Soviet sailors died. No radiation was reported. Last week, the Soviet cruise liner Maxim Gorky rammed the ice pack off <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. None of the 950 passengers were hurt. <PERSON> Johan </PERSON> <PERSON> Baarli </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s Institude for Radiation Hygiene, said preliminary water and air tests show no radiation from the Echo II accident. `` But the tests would not measure radiation aboard ship,'' <PERSON> Baarli </PERSON> said in an interview. Reports said that with its reactor being kept cool with fresh water pumped from a Soviet escort vessel, the damaged submarine was sailing toward its home port in the northern <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` We do n't like the idea of them having to cool the reactor with water from another ship. Even with the reactor shut down, if it loses all cooling the afterheat of the reactor could be enough to cause problems,'' said <PERSON> Gussgard </PERSON>. Officials of this <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> member nation have criticized <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s slowness in warning them of potential danger and express concern about general safety of Soviet submarines <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION>'s Defense Minister <PERSON> Johan </PERSON> <PERSON> Joergen </PERSON> <PERSON> Holst </PERSON> called Monday for a special agreement requiring the Soviets to inform <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> of dangerous situations near its coast. A Soviet Embassy spokesman told the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Dagbladet </ORGANIZATION> today that the Soviets regretted the delay but had not considered the accident threatening enough to warrant a warning. <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> is concerned that 100 nuclear submarines operating out of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fleet </ORGANIZATION> base on the <LOCATION> Kola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>, just over <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s northern border, may be dangerous even in peacetime. The submarines, including about 30 of the older Echo II design, regularly pass through and patrol a narrow, strategically important corridor to the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> that follows <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s coast, a Norwegian defense spokesman said.
