 A. I oppose public financing of these campaigns. I think people should be able to attract private support, and I think participation by individuals in the political process through financial support is very, very important. I do n't want to see eroding out, the eroding out of participation by Americans in the political process. So, I'm opposing, I will oppose and have opposed the public financing of all of these campaigns Now, there are proposals that I'm not prepared to discuss in detail, though I see others have already started dicussing what I might do on Thursday. I will have specific proposals, but _ and I think they'll be fairly far-reaching, because I want to see reform, real reform, and they'll be good proposals. But I'm not prepared to go into what I'm going to do now except to say, I will not support kicking the citizen out of the political process by saying hat a citizen can not financially support the candidate of his or her choice. Q. So if I could follow-up. If the broad outlines of what you are going to do as reported are correct, there's going to be some accusations that they help Republicans more than Democrats. How are you going to respond ... A. Why would anyone make a charge like that against me when I'm looking at it as objectively as I can Let's wait till you see what the _ what it, what it, what the proposals are. I mean, I would be outraged by a suggestion of that nature. Yeah? Q. You and Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> are touring each other's back yards in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. And now that you've finished your foreign policy reviews with regard to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, have you moved any closer to perhaps meeting with the general secretary? A. That _ I would n't say `` closer.'' That matter will be discussed again. It's having been discussed once by the secretary and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>. But I _ so I guess I'd, I'd leave it right there. There will, obviously 