<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A national student group said today it will defy a government ban and march to communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to attend a youth festival. Other students hurled rocks and firebombs at riot police on two campuses Monday. Official <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION> news agency said 15 students were arrested. The chairman of the radical <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> told a news conference he expects 15,000 students to congregate at <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hanyang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> for a march Friday, the eve of the festival. `` We've not given up hope to go to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>,'' said Im Chong-suk. The World Youth Festival will be held in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s capital, <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>, July 1-8. Prosecutors confirmed they issued warrants Monday for the arrest of Im and two other leaders of the radical student group, charging them with violating the National Security Law by talking on the telephone with North Korean students. The law forbids communication with people in an `` anti-state'' body. Im was undeterred. He said South Korean students plan to draft a joint communique with North Korean students and, if they can not get to <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>, details will be arranged through third countries using telephones and facsimile machines. Students holding valid passports and those studying overseas are being encouraged to try to get to <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> through third countries, he said. The <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> government says any who attend without notifying the government or a South Korean Embassy can be prosecuted. <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> accuses <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> of using the festival to stir up dissident movements in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> _ a charge the Noth Korean government denies. The festival is a political and sports event attended mostly by youths from the Third World and communist bloc. At <ORGANIZATION> Hanyang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> Monday, fighting erupted when 200 students screaming anti-government slogans and hurling rocks and firebombs attacked riot police blocking campus gates. About 500 visored police ringed the campus and stopped outsiders from entering. Student leaders said some students from the provinces already were inside. In provincial <LOCATION> Taegu </LOCATION> city, police fired tear gas to disperse 500 students from three schools who attacked them with firebombs and rocks outside <ORGANIZATION> Yongnam </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, according to <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION>. The South Korean agency said 15 students were arrested. South and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> have been bitter rivals since their land was divided at the end of World War II. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> invaded the south in 1950 and the three-year Korean War left more than l million dead on both sides. A truce was never signed and enmity deepened.
