<HEAD>Harbor Pilot Says He Radioed Warnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Oil Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A harbor pilot today said he radioed three warnings to the World Prodigy to change course before the tanker ran aground and spilled 420,000 gallons of oil. But the pilot, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>, told a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard-National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> hearing he could not be certain the message was received because there was a lot of radio interference at the time. The 533-foot Greek tanker hit a reef at the mouth of <LOCATION> Narragansett </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> on Friday after failing to wait for the pilot to board and guide the vessel into port. <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> authorities are investigating whether the ship was past the point at which a pilot is required by state law. Gov. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON> testified that hours after the spill, the captain admitted he was at fault. The governor said he asked <PERSON> Iakovos </PERSON> <PERSON> Georgoudis </PERSON>, `` Why were you in that location which requires a pilot to be on board?'' `` He said, ` That was my mistake,''' <PERSON> DiPrete </PERSON> said. `` He made no bones about it.'' <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> said he first talked with the ship about 4:30 p.m. Friday and that the tanker reported it was about 2 -LCB- miles from the point where <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> was supposed to meet it and guide it into the bay. `` My first words were, ` Aim the vessel more toward the -LRB- <PERSON> Brenton </PERSON> <PERSON> Light </PERSON> -RRB- tower,''' <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> testified. `` That was not correct, so I said ` Head the vessel more toward the tower.' Then I said, ` Keep the red buoy on your starboard bow.''' The pilot said he repeated the warning twice but could not be sure it got through. `` That transmission, there was interference with a lot of small-boat traffic,'' <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> said. He said that interference is common during the summer and called on the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> to do something to free up vital radio channels. Most of the spilled oil had dispersed or evaporated by today and no longer posed much of a threat to the shore, officials said. `` It's going to flush out by itself,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petty </ORGANIZATION> Officer <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON>, overseeing the cleanup at <ORGANIZATION> Hull </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cove </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jamestown </LOCATION>. There had been reports of lobsters killed and several small birds found dead, but officials said those did not appear to be widespread. State Attorney General <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neil </PERSON> seized the ship's records and has begun criminal investigation. He planned to convene a grand jury on Wednesday.
