<HEAD>Five Bulgarian Dissidents Arrested, Emigre Source Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five dissidents have been arrested in <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, but it is unclear when or if they will go on trial, an emigre source reported Tuesday. The source confirmed the arrest in <LOCATION> Sofia </LOCATION> last month of the Rev. <PERSON> Hristofor </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabev </PERSON>, an Orthodox priest from <LOCATION> Veliko </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Turnovo </LOCATION> who founded the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Religious </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION>. It was believed that <PERSON> Sabev </PERSON>, 43, was taken into custody because of his support for religious and human rights in <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, including the Turkish minority's ethnic rights. In early June, authorities also arrested <PERSON> Todor </PERSON> <PERSON> Gagalov </PERSON>, an economist and vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Podkrepa </ORGANIZATION>, an independent intellectuals' union, one of about eight dissident groups that have arisen in <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> recently. Three other leading members of Podkrepa, including <PERSON> Konstantin </PERSON> <PERSON> Trenchev </PERSON>, its president, were arrested last month. Bulgarian government officials said Friday about 50 people were under investigation for their role in ethnic Turkish disturbances last month that Western diplomats say killed 30 people. The clashes with Bulgarian security forces occurred as authorities sought to disperse demonstrators calling for restoration of religious and civil rights of the 1 million-member Turkish minority. More than 70,000 of the ethnic Turks have already left <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> for <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> after the <LOCATION> Sofia </LOCATION> government opened its borders early this month.
