<HEAD>Fire in Test Engine Could Delay Space Shuttle Launch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Engineers examined a space shuttle main engine Tuesday to determine if damage it suffered in a test-firing could delay this summer's launch of the shuttle <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>. `` Engineers have to inspect the engine and look at the data before they can make a decision about <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s launch,'' said <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Drachlis </PERSON>, a space agency spokesman at the <ORGANIZATION> Marshall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Huntsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala </LOCATION>. The failure happened Friday on a test stand at the <ORGANIZATION> Stennis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, during firing of a development engine that has been ignited 23 times over several years to test new parts for future shuttle flights. <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s three main engines already are in place as technicians here prepare it for a launch in late July or early August on a classified <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> mission. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Smelser </PERSON>, head of the engine program at the Marshall center, said <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> needs to determine if the problem involves parts similar to those in <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>'s engines. <PERSON> Drachlis </PERSON> said the test engine operated normally until about 21 minutes into a planned firing of 22 minutes 17 seconds, when there was a sudden shutdown and a fire. During a shuttle launch, the main engines normally fire for about 8 minutes 30 seconds. There was significant damage to several internal parts, <PERSON> Drachlis </PERSON> said. `` The engine did not blow up; it's still fundamentally intact,'' he said. The engine was flown to its manufacturer, the <ORGANIZATION> Rocketdyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Canoga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Drachlis </PERSON> said engineers would take the engine apart for detailed inspection
