<HEAD>Chinese TV Factory OK'd for Venture in South Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Chinese TV factory has signed an agreement with a South Korean company, the first time the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> government has given approval for direct investment by a business from a communist nation, the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Hanzhou </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> TV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Factory </ORGANIZATION> has signed an agreement to invest $ 2.8 million in a joint venture with <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Zhejiang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fuchen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, a ministry spokesman said. Foreign investment in <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> is subject to approval by the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. The spokesman said the joint venture with the factory was expected to produce 580,000 20-inch tubes for color TV sets in 1989, 1.1 million tubes in 1990 and 1.2 million in 1992. The joint venture was expected to export 20 percent of the production to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> through <LOCATION> Zhejiang </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fuchen </LOCATION>, which has invested $ 1.2 million in the venture, the ministry said. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, which has no diplomatic relations with neighboring <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, is trying to expand trade with communist nations to enlarge its markets and ease tension with communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>.
