<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has asked the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to delay the start of the <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> program that was to begin sending <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> volunteers to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> this fall to teach English, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said today. Authorities also ordered two Americans _ a teacher and a student _ to leave the country, apparently for participating in the student-led pro-democracy movement, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> said. Eleven other Americans, detained Monday in <LOCATION> Kunming </LOCATION> and charged with distributing religious tracts, were released and told to leave <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> by Friday, the embassy said. It said the Americans, members of the <ORGANIZATION> Latter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Litchfield </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, would leave in the next day or so. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, group tours to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> involving 43,000 Japanese have been canceled since martial law was declared in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> in May and troops crushed the pro-democracy movement, Japanese officials said. <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> official <PERSON> Tokuji </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakamura </PERSON> said the cancellations cost the agencies $ 60 million in sales. In <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> leaders today called for an embargo on arms sales to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and urged the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> to postpone new loans to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to protest the government's crackdown. The leaders of the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, at their two-day summit, condemned in a statement `` the brutal repression taking place in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.'' Official Chinese media reported today that the steering committee of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s legislature would meet in special session Thursday to endorse the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s tough stance on dissent. Also to be discussed are a draft law on tightening controls over rallies and demonstrations. Plans to discuss a long-pending bill defining the rights and responsibilities of the press have been shelved. The student demonstrations of April and May _ now called the period of turmoil _ called for greater press freedom, and for several weeks the press enjoyed unprecedented leeway in objectively reporting events. But, since political hard-liners gained the upper hand, the press has reverted to its former role as mouthpiece of the party line. The Chinese gave no reason for their request last week for the <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> postponement, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said, saying they just wanted to put the program off `` until a more appropriate time.'' The decision was apparently triggered by continuing tension following the June 4 military crackdown in which soldiers killed hundreds of unarmed protesters in clearing central <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> of student protesters. Martial law remains in effect in most of the capital. Twenty Americans had been scheduled to go to <LOCATION> Sichuan </LOCATION> province in central <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to teach English from this fall, said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official, who would not be further identified. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has criticized <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for cutting off military aid because of the bloody crackdown and for harboring leading dissident <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> <PERSON> Lizhi </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. But `` we're not reading anything retaliatory into'' the <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> postponement, the official said. `` It's not by any means canceled.'' The volunteers began a training program in May to prepare for their assignments in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which would be the 65th nation and first communist country with a Peace Corps program. The two Americans ordered to leave <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> by Friday are a teacher and a student at <ORGANIZATION> Nankai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in the northeastern port of <LOCATION> Tianjin </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> official said on condition of anonymity. Contacted by telephone, a foreign affairs official at the university identified the two as <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Radicia </PERSON>, 25, of <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, Neb.; and <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Qubain </PERSON>, 21, of <LOCATION> Buena </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vista </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION>. The official quoted the pair as saying police had ordered them out of the country for violating unspecified regulations on the behavior of foreigners. The official said <PERSON> Radicia </PERSON> taught business management. Six journalists _ three Britons and three Americans _ have been ordered out of the country since June 4 for ther reporting on the situation. The official media said the <ORGANIZATION> Standing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would hear a report at its session Thursday on `` quelling the counterrevolutionary rebellion.'' The Standing Committee, consisting of about 160 members, meets every few months, usually for about a week, to discuss legislation to be put before the annual full session of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Decision-making power in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> rests with the party, and the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' role has generally been limited to formal approval of laws and government appointments. In recent years, however, it has been given more freedom to delay or revise legislation and to debate national issues.
