<HEAD>Second Nuclear Weapons Test in A Week Finally Detonated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAHUTE MESA, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A nuclear blast up to 12 times more powerful than the bomb dropped on <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> rocked the desert this morning in the second major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> weapons test in a week. The blast registered 4.6 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Earthquake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, said spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Minsch </PERSON>. The test, code-named <LOCATION> Amarillo </LOCATION>, was deemed a success by the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyer </PERSON> said monitors indicated no leak of radiation. The device was detonated 2,100 feet beneath the test range at 8:30 a.m. and had an explosive force of up to 150,000 tons of TNT. The blast that destroyed <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> had an explosive force of 13,000 tons of TNT. Ground zero was three miles from where a test code-named Contact was conducted June 22. That blast measured 5.2 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale. The test was scheduled for Saturday but was repeatedly delayed by unfavorable wind. Tests are not conducted if winds are blowing toward a populated area such as <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> in case radiiation escapes the underground cavity. Both devices were classified as having a range of between 20 and 150 kilotons, the upper limit allowed under treaties with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Today's test was believed to be near the upper limit. When a test is conducted near the upper limits, the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announces the blast in advance and warns managers of highrise buildings in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> not to have workers in precarious positions. Today's test was the seventh announced blast of the year at the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> Test Site and the 694th since testing began in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> in 1951.
