<HEAD>Soviets Pushed 1991 Human Rights Plans at Paris Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Soviet Union used an East-West human rights conference last week to sell itself as host for a follow-up session in 1991. Laboring under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and British threats to boycott the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> conference if sufficient progress in human rights is not made, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> delegation tried to dispel doubts about its sincerity. The month-long Conference on the Human Dimension, which ended Friday, was the first of three on human rights held in the framework of the 1975 <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> accords. Ambassador <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kashlev </PERSON> said his delegation held more than 100 meetings with journalists and human rights groups, assuring a high profile and an `` open and straightforward position'' that `` drew positive response.'' Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> set the tone in a speech May 30 at the 35-nation forum, saying the affirmation of individual rights should be the objective of all countries. A Soviet official later paid his nation's first clear homage to <PERSON> Raoul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallenberg </PERSON>, the Swedish diplomat who saved thousands of Jews in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> in World War II, then disappeared after being arrested by occupying Soviet forces. `` We profoundly regret the death of this noble person,'' said <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Andreyev </PERSON> of the Soviet prosecutor's office. <PERSON> Wallenberg </PERSON>'s fate, he said, `` is a somber page in our history. Over the following month, the affable Soviet delegation laid on news conferences and opened its doors to special interest groups with grievances about human rights abuses in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The Soviets deny they fear a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> boycott of the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> meeting and say their attitude reflects the fruits of President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policies of social and economic reforms. `` It's not an artificial thing,'' said <PERSON> Kashlev </PERSON>. `` Even before the decision on the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> conference, we were the same open people ... It's not just a trick to persuade somebody.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> agreed to attend the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> conference `` in the expectation that progress in human rights would continue'' and that free access by protest groups be guaranteed, said a ranking member of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation, who asked not to be identified. `` We have agreed ... and we're planning to go,'' he said. `` But we would have a very hard time sending a delegation if things moved backward.'' `` The decision has been taken,'' said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> ambassador. `` There is no force in the world that will stop it -LRB- the <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> conference -RRB- from being held.'' With or without the Americans, `` the process of democratization will continue,'' <PERSON> Kashlev </PERSON> said. `` It's not because of their pressure. It's our own internal development. It's <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> who does this, not Mr. <PERSON> Abram </PERSON>,'' he said of <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Abram </PERSON>, head of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. The stakes for <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> are high. Holding the third conference there amounts to an affirmation of Soviet compliance with the principles of the <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> Final Act subscribed to by the nations of the Conference on Security and Cooperation in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The conference includes all European nations except <LOCATION> Albania </LOCATION>, as well as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. The three human rights conferences were decided on at the close of a January meeting in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. The second conference will be held next year in <LOCATION> Copenhagen </LOCATION>, and a final meeting is scheduled for <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> in 1992. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and West European nations have acknowledged broad Soviet progress in human rights under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. While East bloc allies <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> were criticized for human rights abuses, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was praised for progress and a new spirit of cooperation. `` The Soviets have taken some comfort that they are not the worst,'' said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegate. They have used a `` non-confrontational, more tolerant approach than we've seen before,'' he said. `` For quite a long time, our position was ` hands off _ it's our internal affair,''' <PERSON> Kashlev </PERSON> said. `` We have changed completely, much more than the West.''
