UP 8th graf pvs, `Brouwer riled ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION> announced his resignation today in a dispute over the future of the country's biggest ecumenical organization. The Rev. <PERSON> Arie </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brouwer </PERSON>, general secretary of the council since 1985, said the organization is not ready to pursue the unifying goals he set for it. `` The time is not ripe for it,'' he said in announcing he will step down on Friday. The council, which includes most major <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> and Eastern Orthodox churches in the country, has been enmeshed in controversy for three years over departmental accountability and authority, as well as financial difficulties. <PERSON> Brouwer </PERSON>, who came close to being dismissed a month ago, had pressed for closer integration of various council units against stiff resistance by some officials. Their `` dream was different than mine,'' he said. <PERSON> Brouwer </PERSON>, 53, a <ORGANIZATION> Reformed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> clergyman, said the rupture was clarified for him by a 57-57 vote over a move to dismiss him at the council's governing board meeting in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, last month. Since the vote, pressure for <PERSON> Brouwer </PERSON> to step down continued. `` I will be in prayer and fasting over the days and weeks to come,'' <PERSON> Brouwer </PERSON> had said after the vote. <PERSON> Brouwer </PERSON> riled some board members with a scathing report in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, saying recent months had been `` a crucifixion, a journey through hell.'' He said the ecumenical atmosphere has been fouled with `` rumors, innuendo and false charges ... poured forth from the bureaucratic rumor mill,'' public media and religious press. Defending his own leadership style, he said: `` The problem is that I have dared to speak the truth to the will to power. ... The powerful are not accustomed to such behavior and they are outraged. They will not have it.'' The main conflict had come over moves to make the council a more united body functioning as a `` communion of communions,'' with each department sharing proportionately in central administrative costs. That system was strongly resisted by <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the council's relief arm and financially biggest operation. The service had operated somewhat independently and with its own revenues. A furor developed in mid-1988 when the service's executive, the Rev. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, resigned because of conflict with <PERSON> Brouwer </PERSON> over integrating the service more closely with other council units. As a result of the internal stress, general recommedations of a reorganizational committee were approved at the <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> meeting, consolidating the council's 11 units into four. Measures that would give member denominations more direct oversight of the council units were part of the plan, specifics of which were to be worked out in September.
