with reaction.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> told a black audience today that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration wo n't pursue legislation to overturn recent <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions on civil rights. However, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said he would monitor implementation of the rulings and take `` any legislative or executive action that might be required to resolve inequities.'' `` The pursuit and promotion of civil rights in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is more than a legal obligation, it is a moral imperative embodied in our national sense of fairness and justice,'' <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> told the annual convention of Operation PUSH, the civil rights group founded by the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. The high court, adopting some positions advocated by the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> under the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, has restricted affirmative action programs and made it more difficult for plaintiffs to prove discrimination in the workplace. The decisions have prompted calls from some lawmakers to consider legislation to overturn the rulings. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told a news conference today his advisers concluded that none of the rulings has jeopardized the principles of equal opportunity for all Americans. He said if the court's decisions turn out to hamper civil rightrs enforcement, he would consider legislation <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, in his first public pronouncement on the controversial cases, said some viewed the decisions `` as a retreat in the battle for civil rights.'' But, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> asked, do `` these decisions ... stand in conflict with this nation's fundamental commitment to ensure the provision of civil rights of all Americans? Or do these decisions represent attempts by the court to fine-tune the complexities of enforcement of civil rights law in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>?'' <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said the effect of the rulings would not be felt until they are applied in new cases, but that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had asked him to monitor their implementation. `` This responsibility is one I take very seriously and one that the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> will approach consistent with our commitment to the goals of fairness and equality in our quest for equal opportunity,'' <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said. During a discussion following the speech, several panelists expressed disappointment that <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> did n't favor immediate legislation to overturn the high court rulings. `` In the past six days, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has basically repealed Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964,'' said <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Educational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` It disappoints us, to put it mildly, to suggest that we must now wait to see how these decisions work in practice.'' `` We ask the administration to express the same reverence for equal opportunity'' as for the American flag, said employment rights lawyer <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Creiter </PERSON>, referring to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal for a constitutional amendment to overturn the high court's legalization of flag burning. <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Neas </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, an umbrella group of civil rights organizations nationwide, had said the administration's response would be an important test. `` President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has repeatedly stated his commitment to civil rights and to minority outreach efforts. However, a decision to oppose legislation to overturn the recent <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions would be completely incompatible with such a commitment,'' <PERSON> Neas </PERSON> said before <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s speech. `` Indeed, remedial legislation has become the No. 1 priority for everyone committed to equal employment opportunity for all Americans,'' <PERSON> Neas </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> spoke at the invitation of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who hailed the attorney general's commitment to civil rights after the two met at the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Departent </ORGANIZATION> last winter. `` The lights have been turned back on in the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and hopefully the dust will be cleared from the books,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told reporters that day. He was referring to the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's civil rights record, which was roundly criticized by black leaders. As he did after the meeting with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> has repeatedly expressed commitment to `` the full enforcement of civl rights laws ... and the full enjoyment of equal opportunity by all of its citizens.'' But the attorney general has conceded he may have differences with civil rights leaders about achieving those goals. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>, whose nomination to head the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s civil rights division has split the civil rights lobby, was accompanying <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> to the convention A black Republican from <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>' nomination is opposed by several organizations who contend he lacks the necessary legal experience to be the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s civil rights chief. But <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and other black leaders have expressed support, albeit muted in some cases, for the <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> nomination.
