<TEXT>
 Eight women arrested for baring their breasts on a city beach pleaded innocent Tuesday, saying a state law that permits men to go shirtless discriminates against women. Ten women were charged on Saturday with exposure of person, a violation under state law. Two defendants did not enter pleas and were rescheduled to appear Wednesday. The women, dubbed the <ORGANIZATION> Topfree </ORGANIZATION> 10, said the state law that permits men to go shirtless in public is unconstitutional because it discriminates against women. `` Because the law is unjust, I plead not guilty,'' <PERSON> Kathie </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> told Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Manning </PERSON> <PERSON> Regan </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Court </LOCATION>. He scheduled a pre-trial conference for Aug. 1. The women are repeating a 1986 protest, in which seven women were arrested in a city park for going topless and spent a week in court trying to convince a judge that the state nudity law is unfair. In 1986, Judge <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Walz </PERSON> dismissed the charges against the women, saying they were expressing their right to free speech by exposing their breasts as a form of protest. The women have been having `` Topfree Equality Picnics'' for the past four years. In 1987 and 1988 they were not arrested.
