<HEAD>Judges Adhering to Federal Guidelines, Study Finds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Judges are adhering to federal guidelines designed to end disparities in criminal sentences, the chairman of the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Sentencing Commission said Tuesday. More than 82 percent of the sentences handed down by federal judges fall within the guidelines in effect since Nov. 1, 1987, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON> said at a news conference. He said his conclusions were based on a random sample of 25 percent of the guideline cases handled over a 16-month period ending March 31. More than 9 percent of the sentences were below the guidelines and nearly 3 percent above it, he said, adding that more than 5 percent fell below the guidelines because defendants provided substantial assistance to the government. <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON>, a federal appeals court judge, said the system was working well and represented `` a dramatic improvement'' over earlier sentencing. The commission was established because federal judges were giving widely different sentences for similar crimes. The law enacted by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in setting up the panel mandated that defendants convicted of similar crimes receive similar sentences. `` Critics have predicted that guideline sentencing would bring the justice system to its knees, inducing an avalanche of trials by defendants who previously would have pleaded guilty,'' <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON> said. However, he said, more than 90 percent of the more than 7,000 defendants sentenced under the guidelines pleaded guilty.
