<HEAD>Ranks Split On Timber Compromise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Environmentalists today rejected a compromise plan but held the door open for further negotiations with the timber industry over protecting the spotted owl in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerr </PERSON>, conservation director for the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, said there was not enough time to consider the plan. Spokesmen for logging companies said the industry was willing to accept the compromise proposed Saturday by Gov. <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldschmidt </PERSON> and the state's congressional delegation at a so-called `` spotted owl summit'' in <LOCATION> Salem </LOCATION>. The proposal called for a short-term increase in the number of trees that could be cut on federal land in the two states while protecting some of the older forests where the rare Northern spotted owl nests. A statement issued by environmental groups said they could not accept the timber harvest figures in the compromise without more information. The congressional delegation had given both sides until this morning to accept the plan. The deadline was set to allow <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> congressmen to attach a rider to an appropriations bill that comes up in a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee Wednesday. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Spence </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, said the timber industry reluctantly accepted the plan. The alternative was `` economic chaos,'' <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> said in a statement. `` The simple truth is that less timber means fewer jobs,'' <PERSON> Spence </PERSON> said.
