 A city councilman faced a recall election today for getting a tough new anti-smoking ordinance passed. The ordinance sponsored by Councilman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> banned most indoor smoking in public places as of April 19. It led a smokers' - rights group to gather enough signatures to force today's recall election, the first involving an <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION> Critics have also charged that <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> votes his personal views and ignores the wishes of the people he represents. `` He's got an insatiable ego and is arrogant, and his usefulness has long since expired,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowden </PERSON>, an organizer of recall campaign. <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>, 41, said he sponsored the bill because polls showed most people in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION> favored smoking restrictions. He said he has a politics-for-the-people attitude but ca n't please everyone all the time. <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON> will lose his seat if a majority of the voters in his district choose to remove him. In addition, at least 1,943 would have to vote against him, half the number of votes cast in the 1987 election in which he won his seat. The American Smokers Alliance, a national smokers' rights group, said <PERSON> Chapman </PERSON>'s defeat could deter local governments from getting on the anti-smoking bandwagon.
