<FIRST>r w AM-S&amp;Ls-JunkBonds     06-27 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Junk Bonds,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Showdown Brewing in Congress Over Junk Bonds and S&amp;Ls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The junk bond market, already troubled by the prospect of an economic slowdown, could suffer a heavy blow if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> adopts legislation forcing savings and loans to sell the high-risk, high-yield securities, economists say. Nevertheless, members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> upset about the wave of corporate takeovers and leveraged buyouts are determined to push thrifts out of the lucrative, but speculative, investment. `` The question ... is simple,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Leach </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>. `` Should the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> taxpayer subsidize leveraged buyouts, takeover artists and large corporate mergers?'' <PERSON> Leach </PERSON> is one of the chief backers of a provision, sponsored by Rep. <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorgan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.D. </LOCATION>, in House-passed <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L legislation. It would forbid thrifts from buying junk bonds and force those that already own them to sell within two years. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> version is more lenient. It maintains the current rule restricting the junk bond holdings of federally chartered S & amp; Ls to 11 percent of assets. It extends the limit to state-chartered institutions, but allows them to exceed it if they can come up with extra capital. A House-Senate conference begins work in two weeks to resolve the many differences, including the provisions affecting junk bonds, in comprehensive legislation to bail out out and reform the S & amp; L industry. High-yield, high-risk bonds, which are often used to finance hostile corporate raids and management buyouts, are nicknamed junk bonds because they have no or a low credit rating. Commercial banks already are forbidden to invest in the bonds, but thrifts have been allowed to buy them since the early 1980s. Relatively few thrifts own junk bonds _ only 161 S & amp; Ls in 36 states, a little more than 5 percent of all S & amp; Ls, according to a report this spring by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' auditing agency Most of those have relatively small investments. Ten thrifts account for three-quarters of the industry's investment, and only seven have junk bond portfolios exceeding the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s proposed limit. But those numbers, according to economists, understate the extent of thrift involvement in junk bonds and the potential ripple effects of <PERSON> Dorgan </PERSON>'s amendment. Between 1985 and 1988, S & amp; L junk bond holdings increased by 136 percent to $ 13.2 billion _ representing about 8 percent of the entire junk bond market, according to the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>. Economists warn that if the <PERSON> Dorgan </PERSON> amendment becomes law, junk bond prices likely will fall and investors, including the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls themselves, will get stuck for the losses. `` I think it's going to be very painful for a lot of these thrifts,'' said economist <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> of <PERSON> Donaldson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lufkin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jenrette </PERSON>. `` Investors who hold junk bonds are going to have to monitor this legislation very, very carefully.'' Those who defend allowing thrifts to own junk bonds say such investments have been unfairly criticized. For all practical purposes, a thrift buying a junk bond is taking no more risk than a thrift making a commercial loan, they say. Secondly, they say, junk bonds offer high returns and they allow <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls in economically troubled regions to diversify by purchasing bonds from companies in healthy regions and industries. Economist <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Getman </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> WEFA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a <PERSON> Bala </PERSON> <PERSON> Cynwyd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, consulting firm, said junk bonds have been among the most profitable activities for thrifts. WEFA studied thrifts and junk bonds for the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Access </ORGANIZATION>, a group representing junk bond issuers and investors. Junk bond critics say the bonds have never been tested by a recession, when losses from defaults are likely to rise, offsetting profits from high-interest earnings. They also say extensive junk bond investment by thrifts diverts money from home mortgages and could allow collusion between S & amp; Ls and securities firms selling the bonds. The largest S & amp; L investor in junk bonds is <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, which owns about $ 4 billion, representing 35 percent of its portfolio. According to published reports, the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has been investigating allegedly unlawful trading arrangements between <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest underwriter of high yield securities. `` Junk bond holdings are one of the areas of most abuse,'' said economist <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Aubrey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lanston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a government securities dealer in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` I as taxpayer do n't want to be the ultimate guarantor of a sweetheart deal between an <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L and an investment firm.''
