<HEAD>Soviets Buy Additional 400,000 Metric Tons of U.S. Wheat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has bought an additional 400,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat for delivery this year under the long-term grain agreement between the two countries, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. Officials said the sale, by unidentified private exporters, was a straight commercial transaction and did not involve subsidies under the department's Export Enhancement Program. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has bought more than 4.2 million tons of wheat under <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> arrangements for 1988-89 delivery, the most recent being 96,000 tons announced on June 23. Although the Soviets had virtually used up the previous <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> allocation, a new deal for an additional 1.5 million tons of wheat was announced May 2. Officials said <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> still has 814,200 tons available under the program. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat. According to the latest <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> five-day average, the price of wheat has been $ 3.85 per bushel, meaning the latest sale of approximately 14.7 million bushels could have a farm value of around $ 56 million. Under EEP arrangements, private exporters can sell <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commodities at reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition in selected overseas markets and then collect free government surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies. The sale announced Tuesday boosted to more than 21.2 million tons the amount of grain <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has bought for delivery in the sixth year of the agreement, which began last Oct. 1. Of that, corn makes up nearly 16.2 million tons, and wheat, more than 5 million tons. In addition, the Soviets have bought 442,500 tons of soybeans; 1.35 million tons of soybean meal; and more than 1 million tons of grain sorghum.
