<HEAD>U.S. Judge Orders HUD, Boston, State To Combat Housing Bias</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has ordered the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, the state and the city to work harder to eliminate racial discrimination in housing in metropolitan <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. The ruling by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> stems from a lawsuit filed 11 years ago by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Colored People against <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Dianne </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkerson </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> called the ruling `` a blockbuster _ a whole new world.'' `` This really is a challenge,'' Ms. <PERSON> Wilkerson </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` In the end it's a challenge to -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> Secretary -RRB- <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> has said fair housing is a challenge for his administration. If that's true, they wo n't appeal. <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> Roundtree </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, said agency attorneys were reviewing the ruling and had not decided whether to appeal. The <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has found that eight of 10 blacks who look for a home to rent or buy encounter discrimination, Ms. <PERSON> Wilkerson </PERSON> said. Friday's ruling gives them more means to fight back, she said. From 1977 to 1982, <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said in his ruling, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> broke federal law by failing to use its grant programs to produce an adequate supply of affordable integrated housing and failing to require effective fair housing enforcement by the city. `` The conditions, exacerbated by <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s pattern of inaction, apparently continue to exist and are currently remediable,'' the ruling said. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>'s ruling orders: _ <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> to require that all landlords who get federal aid participate in programs that market suburban housing to low-income minorities. _ <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> to create a Housing Opportunity Clearinghouse that lists available public housing. _ The state to give the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fair </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> legal authority to issue subpoenas, levy fines and initiate civil actions against discrimination. In 1985, <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said he agreed with the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> suit, finding that <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> was aware that <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> had a history of racial bias in housing and that its acute shortage of low-income family housing affected blacks more than whites. However, he dismissed the lawsuit then, saying he lacked authority to review and correct the agency's practices. In 1987, an appeals court said <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> did have authority, and ordered him to reopen the case. Mayor <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> said Tuesday he welcomed the decision and has supported many similar remedies since becoming mayor in 1984. <PERSON> Marcia </PERSON> <PERSON> Hertz </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the Executive Office of Communities and Development, the state housing agency, praised the ruling. `` It actually mirrors the state policies already in place. Our programs and policies all have strong affirmative action components.'' Ms. <PERSON> Roundtree </PERSON> said, `` If you ask whether there's been some improvement in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> since 1978, from a public housing standpoint, our survey and monitoring report in 1987 showed there are still some problems. `` We're not 100 percent where everybody has equal housing but we're moving in that direction, it's probably not as much as the judge wanted.'' Metropolitan <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> refers to an area of 2.8 million people in about 110 municipalities. While 13 percent of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s 573,000 people are black, there are no current figures available on the percentage in the metropolitan area.
</TEXT>
