<HEAD>Amending Constitution is Difficult _ Deliberately</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Flag Burning Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Amending the Constitution is a difficult process. Thousands of amendments have been proposed, but in more than 200 years only 26 have been ratified. There are two ways to amend the Constitution, one initiated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and one by the state legislatures. Under the Constitution's Article V, a proposed amendment originating in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must be approved by two-thirds votes in both houses. It then must be approved by 38 state legislatures. Two-thirds of the state legislatures may call for a constitutional convention. Any amendment approved by that convention must then be ratified by three-fourths of the states.
</TEXT>
