<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Souther </PERSON> may have been a Soviet spy, but it's unlikely he was a <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> mole who infiltrated this country, his former associates said Tuesday after <PERSON> Souther </PERSON>'s death was reported in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Rather, he was a rambuctious young American who satisfied his craving for attention by defecting to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> three years ago, a decision that may have cost him his life, they said. `` They used him like a spider playing with a moth and when they were going to finish with him, they finished with him,'' said <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Fahey </PERSON>, a professor's wife who knew <PERSON> Souther </PERSON> when he was an Old Dominion University student. <PERSON> Souther </PERSON>, 32, was a former <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> intelligence specialist who disappeared shortly after he graduated from <ORGANIZATION> ODU </ORGANIZATION> in May 1986 with a degree in Russian. He appeared on Soviet television last July and said he had defected. The Soviet military newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday that <PERSON> Souther </PERSON> was a <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> agent named <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Orlov </PERSON> and that he died unexpectedly June 22. `` There's some attempt to imply that he was really a Soviet-born citizen and became a mole, but that was never really stated and I do n't believe it's true,'' said <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Kessler </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> author who is writing a book on <PERSON> Souther </PERSON>. `` He was in fact a very successful spy,'' <PERSON> Kessler </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from his home in <LOCATION> Potomac </LOCATION>. `` He was an American mole. It's possible that he took this Russian name a