<HEAD>Abortion-Consent Law Argued Before State Supreme Court</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s privacy laws should be extended to minors, a lawyer told the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday in the case of a teen-ager forced to ask a judge to allow an abortion without parental consent. `` The statute clearly fails to protect a minor's privacy right,'' attorney <PERSON> Jerri </PERSON> <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> told the justices. `` A minor who is pregnant has a right to submit to any medical procedure except abortion under <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> law. `` There is no question it should be applied to the minor's abortion decision,'' Ms. <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> told reporters later The <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> law requires unmarried minors to get permission from their parents or a judge before having an abortion. The case argued Tuesday began when Ms. <PERSON> Blair </PERSON>'s client, a 15-year-old known only as `` T.W.,'' did not want to tell her parents about her pregnancy _ then in its 11th week _ and sought judicial permission for an abortion. A <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> judge denied her request last month, saying the state law was vague and unworkable. An appeals court then ruled the law unconstitutional, and a series of legal maneuvers landed the case in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, which returned the case to state justices without comment. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has left the law unenforceable until the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> high court reviews it. Suporters of the law contend it protects the unborn and the right of parents to supervise their children. `` When you elevate the right of privacy over the right to life, you have elevated an inferior right over a superior right,'' said <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Connor </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION> attorney for <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> Right to Life. `` Without the right to life, there is no right to privacy.'' Attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bopp </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of Terre Haute, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, who served as guardian for the fetus, argued that minors are not mature enough to make decisions about abortion. `` I do n't believe the people of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> intended to subvert parental rights -LRB- or -RRB- to subvert the state's traditional interest in protecting innocent human life, and withdraw the ability of the state to protect vulnerable minors when they adopted the 1980 <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> right of privacy,'' <PERSON> Bopp </PERSON> said. A ruling by the seven justices could be weeks away as the court begins its annual vacation period next month. The court's decision could affect thousands of unmarried pregnant teens and possibly set a broad precedent, attorneys said. Similar privacy issues dominate a case pending before the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> and the original 1973 <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> decision giving women the right to have abortions. Before <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s parental consent law was declared unconstitutional, 60 teen-agers received judicial permission for an abortion.
