<HEAD>Amnesty International Condemns U.S. Death Penalty Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that rulings by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> upholding the death penalty for youthful or retarded offenders are a step backward for human rights. In two 5-4 votes, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said Monday the Constitution's ban on cruel and unusual punishment does not prohibit execution of people who committed crimes as young as 16, or adults with the reasoning capacity of children. `` The imposition of death sentences on juvenile offenders was in clear contravention of international human rights treaties and standards including the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Covenant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, both of which the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government signed in 1977 but has not ratified,'' <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said. The London-based group, which won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1977, said the death penalty was particularly inappropriate for individuals who had not attained full physical or emotional maturity at the time of their crimes. `` To impose the death penalty in such cases, whether as retribution or as an intended deterrent, violates basic principles of humanity,'' the group's statement said. <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> noted that 72 countries that retain the death penalty have abolished it for criminals under the age of 18, including the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> are among the countries that have executed people who were under 18 at the time of their crimes, <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> said.
