<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fame </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday that the board had no qualms about accepting $ 35,000 from a cigarette company to keep the financially ailing museum open In fact, <PERSON> Sally </PERSON> <PERSON> Parr </PERSON> said the board of the <LOCATION> Seneca </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, museum approached <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cos. </ORGANIZATION> and was rateful for its help. But the decision to accept the money has drawn stinging criticism from a leading feminist who said cigarettes are killing women. `` Women's organizations are going to have to stop taking money from the merchants of death,'' <PERSON> Molly </PERSON> <PERSON> Yard </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday. <PERSON> Parr </PERSON> said at a news conference Tuesday that the $ 10,000 in cash and $ 25,000 worth of public relations and fund-raising services from <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> gave the museum `` a starting point to move on.'' <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Posie </PERSON> <PERSON> DiSesa </PERSON> said the company did n't expect any promotion from the museum in exchange for the donation The museum board launched an urgent fund-raising drive June 13, saying the Hall of Fame would close if $ 100,000 was n't raised by June 30. The board announced Monday that the $ 35,000 donation from <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> and a $ 100,000 <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> grant would keep the shrine alive. The private, non-profit educational institute was $ 68,000 in debt before the drive. The National Women's Hall of Fame, founded in 1968, is in an old bank building in the upstate <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> village that bills itself as `` The Birthplace of Women's Rights.'' Women's rights pioneer <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Cady </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON> and 300 other women met there in 1848 to issue a `` Declaration of Sentiments,'' which demanded the right to vote, equal schooling and wages. Despite her displeasure with the <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> donation, <ORGANIZATION> Yard </ORGANIZATION> said it was important to keep the hall open. `` It's the only place in the country where there's any attempt to keep records of leading <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> women,'' she said.
