<HEAD>Bush Urges Americans to Thank God for Their Freedom on July Fourth</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Flag Burning, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> urged Americans Tuesday to thank God for their freedom on the Fourth of July and celebrate `` the resounding success'' of their 213-year-old experiment in democracy. `` To every American citizen, here and abroad, Happy Fourth of July!'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said in an Independence Day message. `` The Fourth of July is a day to pause and thank God that men such as <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> had the strength, courage and insight to forge a nation predicated upon the noble ideal, ` that all men are created equal, that they are endowed by their creator with certain unalienable rights,''' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` After 213 years, Americans can say that the experiment is a resounding success,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` The Fourth of July is a time to rejoice in this success, which has inspired all who seek to break the shackles of totalitarian rule and breathe in the life-giving air of liberty.'' As a boy growing up in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, `` the Fourth of July represented the best of holidays. It held the promise of parades, picnics and fireworks,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` More important, however, it introduced a small boy to the promise of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' said the president. `` Everywhere I turned, I would see the red, white and blue of our flag. `` As a grew older, I realized that the flag has reminded generations of Americans how fortunate we are to live in a free and democratic republic,'' said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who said Tuesday he will seek a constitutional amendment to overturn a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that struck down flag desecration laws. `` It is a banner respected around the world.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will leave Friday for his oceanfront home in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, to spend the holiday with family and friends. He will return to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Wednesday July 5.
