<HEAD>Grosz Says He Wants To Quit As Party Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Karoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, his power curbed in a new four-man leadership dominated by reformers, was quoted Tuesday as saying he plans to resign as <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief next year. <PERSON> Mai </PERSON> <PERSON> Nap </PERSON>, an independent afternoon daily, quoted <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> as saying in an interview he `` will no longer be general secretary'' after parliamentary elections scheduled for 1990. He has held the post 13 months. `` We have to make room for the younger generation,'' the paper quoted him as saying. `` Obviously, I'll continue to be engaged in politics at some level, but I never again want to be a general secretary.'' <PERSON> Rezsoe </PERSON> <PERSON> Nyers </PERSON>, father of pioneering economic reforms in the late 1960s, was chosen as party chairman Saturday, and a four-man Presidium was formed to run the party until the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> scheduled for Oct. 7. The paper quoted <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> as saying the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> had `` agreed that we will need to hold -LRB- another -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> after the elections as well. It's obvious that there will be a new balance of forces and a new leadership.'' <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON>, considered a centrist, has lost standing recently with contradictory statements. He angered other leading Communists, and many other Hungarians, when he said on television May 30 there was no need to rehabilitate <PERSON> Imre </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON>, who led the 1956 uprising crushed by Soviet tanks, because <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON>'s execution was `` not a party decision.'' A day later, party issued a statement that described <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON> as a forerunner of reform and amounted to de facto rehabilitation. <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON> since has been reburied with honors. <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> replaced <PERSON> Janos </PERSON> <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON> as party chief in May 1988, heading a new leadership that seemed to strike a balance between reformers and more orthodox Communists. As reformers gained the upper hand over conservatives wary of relinquishing power, <PERSON> Grosz </PERSON> jockeyed unsuccessfully for a middle ground. Communists and democratic opposition groups agreed to cooperate in drafting legislation to govern the first multiparty elections in more than 40 years, and work began June 13. The government has said elections will be held by June of next year, but there have been increasing calls for the date to be advanced.
