<HEAD>House Approves Compact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House on Tuesday endorsed and sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> legislation that would give final approval to a self-government plan for the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> islands of <PERSON> Palau </PERSON>. The measure, passed on a voice vote, also provides final authorization for spending of $ 238 million over the next five years, including an immediate $ 36 million payment to cover <PERSON> Palau </PERSON>'s debt for a power plant. `` This is a highly responsible act for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Udall </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ariz </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> The measure `` brings an honorable end to a very difficult chapter in the history of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Lugo </PERSON>, the non-voting House delegate from the <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Palau </PERSON> is the last of four parts of the Trust Territory of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, created following World War II, to define its political status. The plan, called the <ORGANIZATION> Compact </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, provides self-government in all areas except defense, which is reserved for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> also retains a 50-year right to establish a military base on <PERSON> Palau </PERSON> should it need an alternative to its current bases in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Palau </PERSON> itself has failed in six referendums to approve the compact, and the bill provides another $ 200,000 to hold a seventh referendum. The island nation has been troubled by political corruption, crippling debts and fiscal mismanagement, drug abuse and crumbling public facilities. The legislation would create a anti-drug program for <PERSON> Palau </PERSON> and establishes controls for the spending of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid money. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> acted despite warnings from Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Frenzel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Minn </LOCATION>., who argued that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> does n't have the money to spend `` We are playing fast and loose with our budget agreement. We are squeezing things in and declaring them emergencies,'' he said. In a separate action, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> also approved and sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> a bill establishing regular diplomatic relations with two other former <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> trusteeships, the <LOCATION> Marshall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Micronesia </LOCATION>. The measure would elevate the status of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> envoys in those two island groups to ambassador.
