<HEAD>Burma Warns of Action Against Unauthorized Publications</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>'s military government said on government radio and television Monday that it will act under martial law to stop unauthorized organizations from printing and distributing books and pamphlets. The announcement said there were `` 48 unauthorized organizations engaged in activities aimed at disturbing peace and tranquility in the country and also printing and distributing pamphlets illegally.'' The government added that `` 51 similar unauthorized organizations are also operating in the name of students organizations.'' `` Legally registered political and other organizations can apply for registration under the ... law.. and ask for exemption to print and distribute books and pamphlets purely for election purposes,'' it said It said 226 political parties were registered with the <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and 57 social organizations with the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> and Religious Affairs. The military government, which seized power last September, has promised a general election next year, <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> rebel sources in <LOCATION> Mae </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sot </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, said up to 900 Burmese soldiers backed by mortar and artillery fire attacked <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> guerrilla positions close to the Thai frontier before dawn Tuesday. The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said heavy fighting followed at the <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> base of <LOCATION> Pa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Loo </LOCATION>, about eight miles south of <LOCATION> Mae </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sot </LOCATION>. Soldiers fired hundreds of mortar and artillery shells into <PERSON> Pa </PERSON> <PERSON> Loo </PERSON> and a nearby camp at <LOCATION> Kaw </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ra </LOCATION>, they said. The <LOCATION> Moei </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> separates the camps from <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>. More than 50 shells fell into <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Pa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Loo </LOCATION> and Burmese machine-gun fire hit three houses and a <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> temple in <LOCATION> Mae </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kane </LOCATION> <LOCATION> village </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Thai </LOCATION> border patrol police said, adding that <LOCATION> Thai </LOCATION> security forces returned fire. No casualty reports were available. The Karens are among a dozen ethnic groups in <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> which for 40 years have fought for greater autonomy. The Karens, with about 8,000 armed fighters, are the largest group. Government forces began a major campaign against the Karens last October.
