<HEAD>Severe Thunderstorms In Texas And Louisiana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Showers and thunderstorms from the remnants of Tropical Storm <PERSON> Allison </PERSON> spread heavy rain Tuesday over southeastern <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and western <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, and thunderstorms were scattered along the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. In the East, <ORGANIZATION> Baltimore </ORGANIZATION> posted a record-tying high of 98 degrees. The highest sustained wind speed associated with the tropical depression was near 35 mph, with gusts to 45 mph in heavy squalls along the extreme upper <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> coast. Tides 2 to 3 feet above normal along the upper <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> coast and the western coast of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> were expected to slowly decrease during the night. Heavier rain amounts for the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included 3.95 inches at <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Charles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, 2.65 inches at <LOCATION> Shreveport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, 2.57 inches at <LOCATION> Lufkin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and 1.27 inches at <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Polk </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>. A thunderstorm in southwestern <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> unleashed a tornado at Hackberry that destroyed three to four houses and damaged 12 others, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. A thunderstorm at <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Charles </LOCATION> produced high wind which damaged the roof of a hangar and blew the roofs off two smaller buildings. The <LOCATION> Shreveport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, fire department reported that it rescued a woman whose car slipped into a flooded irrigation ditch. Rescue personnel said she was in good condition at a local hospital. Ahead of a cold front in the upper <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, showers and thunderstorms were scattered from the middle <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> to the central Appalachians, the upper <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> and the lower Great Lakes region. Thunderstorms packing high winds damaged houses, uprooted trees and knocked down power lines in <LOCATION> Wapakoneta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. Officials said no injuries were reported. `` At first it started real hard rain. You could n't see across the street,'' said <LOCATION> Wapakoneta </LOCATION> resident <PERSON> Adis </PERSON> <PERSON> Roop </PERSON>. ` Then here come the trees. I ran for the house, I could n't hardly get through the door. The suction pulled me back out.'' Showers and thunderstorms also were scattered from the central Gulf Coast to southern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56 degrees at <LOCATION> Bremerton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, to 102 at <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz </LOCATION>. The nation's low was not supplied by the weather service For Wednesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast from eastern <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and eastern <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> states. Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast from <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. Highs in the 70s were predicted from northern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION>, and from western <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> to the northern <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and along the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> coast; in the lower 90s across the southern half of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> region, and across much of the area from southern and central interior <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to the great Plains region; and above 100 degrees in the desert Southwest.
