<UNK>Brazilian Police File Charges Against Super-Investor</UNK>
<DATELINE>SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A multimillionaire investor linked to a financial scandal that shook <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s stock markets has been charged on two counts of financial wrongdoing, police said Tuesday. Police questioned <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON> Monday night about his role in the scandal, but the charges filed were unrelated to the crisis, which led to the closing of six brokerage houses, police spokesman <PERSON> Mauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Ament </PERSON> said from <LOCATION> Brasilia </LOCATION>, the capital. <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON> is accused of trying to illegally take dollars out of the country in 1987 and of violating the Financial System Law in 1983, <PERSON> Ament </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Ament </PERSON> said that in December, 1987, police at <LOCATION> Sao </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paulo </LOCATION>'s International Airport found $ 20,000 in <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON>' suitcase as he was about to board a plane for <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> By law, Brazilians then were only allowed to take $ 1,000. In 1983, a construction firm owned by <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON> borrowed the equivalent of $ 12 million from the <ORGANIZATION> Sogeral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, of which he was a major shareholder. `` This was a violation of the Financial System Law, which prohibits this kind of transaction,'' <PERSON> Ament </PERSON> said. The spokesman said that if convicted on the charges, <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON> faces an 11-year jail term. Federal police also questioned <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON> on his alleged role in the stock market scandal that broke June 9, but <PERSON> Ament </PERSON> said there was still insufficeint evidence to bring charges against the investor. <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON> bounced $ 31 million in checks to pay for highly speculative deals on the <ORGANIZATION> Rio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Janeiro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Brazilian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. On June 12, the government closed all of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s nine stock markets to avoid panic among investors. <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON> was prohibited from leaving the country. The market reopened the next day. The government has closed six brokerage houses involved in the scandal, including one owned by <PERSON> Elmo </PERSON> <PERSON> Camoes </PERSON>, former president of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Camoes </PERSON> resigned shortly before his brokerage was closed. <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON>, a Lebanese immigrant whose business interests range from mining and farming to real estate and insurance, is a common sight in Brazilian society pages. In 1984 he hosted <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> arms merchant <PERSON> Adnan </PERSON> <PERSON> Khashoggi </PERSON> on a visit to <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. The Commodity Futures Trading Commission of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> also has linked <PERSON> Nahas </PERSON> with <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> billionaires <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> in their ill-fated try to corner the world's silver bullion market
