<HEAD>DC Council OKs Income Limit for City Politicians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> approved legislation Tuesday to sharply limit outside income for city officeholders, a move some say is designed to prevent the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> from running for mayor. The bill, sponsored by council member <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> and approved on an 11-2 vote, sets a $ 10,000 limit on income from speeches for the mayor and council chairman and includes an amendment by council Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> that limits the mayor or council chairman to $ 10,000 income from book royalties. Both <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> and <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON> are running for mayor in the 1990 race. Incumbent <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> has not said whether he will seek re-election. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who earns most of his income from speeches, has not ruled out running for the $ 82,500-per-year post. `` I am awfully suspicious when two announced candidates put together legislation to keep someone from running,'' said council member <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. `` We can ... say that this is a <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> bill for sure,'' said council member <PERSON> Nadine </PERSON> <PERSON> Winter </PERSON>. `` We have railroaded a piece of legislation in 19 days only because the political campaign is heating up, and it seems to me we have a problem here.'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> and council member <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> voted against the measure. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> denied the bill was meant to keep <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> off the ballot and said he began working on it after constituents complained last year when the council voted itself a pay raise. Council member H.R. <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> said the honoraria limit would be an unfamiliar concept for most city officials. `` From what I hear in the community, most people would pay us $ 10,000 only to be quiet,'' <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON> said.
