<HEAD>Most of PSA Air Crash Cases Settled Just Before Final Arguments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The families of 38 of the 42 people killed when a fired airline employee brought down a jetliner in December 1987 settled their cases out of court on Tuesday. The settlements came just before final arguments were to be heard in the liability trial against <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> and others. Damage cases brought by the families of two passengers, a flight attendant and the pilot remain. Families who did not request confidentiality said settlements ranged from $ 200,000 to $ 3.7 million, attorneys said. The total payment was less than $ 37 million but more than $ 20 million. Evidence presented during the trial included allegations of lax security at both <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> international airports that allowed fired <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> employee <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> to board <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> Flight 1771 with a .44 - caliber Magnum `` I think we brought out how bad it was,'' said plaintiff attorney <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Wecht </PERSON>, referring to airport security. `` Among other things, this was the first public hearing of this airplane crash. ... I think the public had a right and a need to know about this kind of disaster.'' A telephone call seeking comment from lead defense counsel <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Manfredi </PERSON> was not immediately returned. Forty-three people, including <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, died in the Dec. 7, 1987, crash. Federal investigators concluded that midway through the flight, <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> shot his supervisor, then entered the cockpit and shot the crew. Minutes later, the BAe-146 four-engine plane slammed into a hillside north of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Luis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Obispo </LOCATION> in an explosive crash. There were no survivors. <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> <PERSON> Foreman </PERSON>, who represented the families of crew members killed in the crash, said the most damaging testimony in the trial came from former <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> employee <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Drabik </PERSON>, who loaned <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> the gun used in the shootings and was a <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> supervisor in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> at the time. <PERSON> Drabik </PERSON> testified that in November he loaned the gun and 12 rounds of ammunition to <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, a longtime friend, at <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>'s request. <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> had already been fired by <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> for allegedly stealing $ 69 from a petty cash box. <PERSON> Drabik </PERSON> said that on the day he loaned <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> the gun at the airport he helped him get it through security by walking through an employee bypass at the metal detector station while <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> walked through the detectors. Although <PERSON> Drabik </PERSON> insisted that he did not carry the gun through for <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, he could not explain how <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> could pass through the detectors and not set them off. `` Not one juror we talked to later said they believed that,'' said <PERSON> Foreman </PERSON>. `` It was the most damaging testimony for <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>. An employee had knowingly violated security.'' Other testimony came from experts on how <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> managed to sneak a gun aboard Flight 1771 at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> International. Both sides agreed that <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> used an unreturned employee identification badge to move unchallenged through the airport, but his route to the plane with the gun was disputed. Plaintiffs contended <PERSON> Burke </PERSON> could have simply flashed his identification badge at security guards and used a bypass to avoid metal detectors. Since the crash, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> has tightened requirements for airline employees passing through security areas and regulation of identification badge issues. The settlements came before closing arguments or jury deliberations began in the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> case overseen by Judge <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryburn </PERSON>. Defendants included <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, its parent company <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>, the city <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airports </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ogden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION>, the private firm that handles metal detection and passenger screening stations at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. By agreement, the <ORGANIZATION> Airports </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> was dismissed as a defendant by all plaintiffs. <PERSON> Wecht </PERSON>, one of the plaintiffs' attorneys, suggested that the remaining cases might eventually be settled out of court as well. `` It was n't feasible for them to settle at this time,'' said <PERSON> Foreman </PERSON>, who refused to elaborate.
