<HEAD>Head of Church Council Quits, His ``Dream'' For It Rebuffed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Churches </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday he's quitting because `` ecumenical dreams'' for the council as a more unifying movement have been blocked. The Rev. <PERSON> Arie </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brouwer </PERSON> said that in recent struggles over council objectives, `` differences in dreams led to the sharpness of the conflict,'' with him favoring fuller integration of the council's operational units. `` I can do no more in this position to fulfill'' that goal, he told a conference. <PERSON> Brouwer </PERSON>, 53, said he would step down Friday as the council's general secretary, a post he has held for four and a half years, the last two embroiled in turmoil over future council directions The council, the country's largest ecumenical organization, includes most major Protestant and Eastern Orthodox denominations totaling more than 40 million members. <PERSON> Brouwer </PERSON>, a tall, quiet-spoken Midwesterner from <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> and a clergyman in the Reformed Church in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, emphasized he was not leaving the council office `` in a spirit of anger or bitterness.'' The conflict over goals boiled to a near breaking point at a May meeting in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, of the council's governing board, which split evenly _ 57 votes to 57 _ over a move to oust <PERSON> Brouwer </PERSON>. He said his resignation `` is a direct result of events precipitated'' at that meeting, which initiated steps to consolidate 11 council units into four, each run by church representatives largely independent of other units. <PERSON> Brouwer </PERSON> said this essentially perpetuated the past loosely linked units, mostly setting their own policies. He had clashed sharply with <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGA