 life together that now deprive our community of <PERSON> Arie </PERSON>'s leadership.'' The Rev. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> McClurg </PERSON>, a Presbyterian and the council's titular president, said there has been a `` great deal of hurt'' in the conflict, and the council wanted to move forward toward greater unity, but she added: `` This was not the right time We did n't learn to do it quickly enough. We've had some rough sledding. But we have n't given up.'' The Rev. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> and the council's <LOCATION> Washinton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> public-policy representative, was named as the council's acting general secretary until <PERSON> Brouwer </PERSON>'s successor is chosen
