<HEAD>Second Nuclear Weapons Test in A Week Finally Detonated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAHUTE MESA, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A nuclear weapons test that had been delayed by fickle wind conditions shook the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> desert Tuesday with an explosion several times the force of the <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> atomic bomb. The blast registered 4.6 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale of ground motion at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Earthquake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, according to spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Minsch </PERSON>. Monitors atop highrise hotels in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>, 100 miles from ground zero, registered the blast. But the readings were not as distinct as with some previous tests. The test, code-named <LOCATION> Amarillo </LOCATION>, was the second major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear weapons test in six days. Energy Department officials deemed the latest shot a success. The device was detonated 2,100 feet beneath the surface of <LOCATION> Pahute </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mesa </LOCATION> on the sprawling desert test range and had an explosive force of up to 150,000 tons of TNT. The blast that destroyed <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION> had an explosive force of 13,000 tons of TNT. `` The seismograph needle is swinging wildly from side to side,'' <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyer </PERSON> said as he monitored the blast in a control center 30 miles from ground zero. The test was originally scheduled for Saturday, then delayed several times because of unfavorable wind conditions. It was rescheduled for Sunday, then delayed again for the same reason. Tests are not conducted if winds are blowing toward a populated area such as <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> in the event that nuclear radiation escapes the underground cavity where the nuclear device is detonated. <PERSON> Boyer </PERSON> said monitoring equipment surrounding ground zero indicated there was no leak of radiation.
