<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee staff analysis concluded Tuesday that running the controversial <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> nuclear power plant on <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> would be cheaper that shutting it down, contrary to an analysis by state regulators. After hearing some of the report's conclusions, Chairman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> characterized the study, which he had not seen, as `` baloney.'' The analysis was released as the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Atomic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Licensing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> decided that it was acceptable to use pole-mounted sirens on trucks to notify nearby <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> residents of an emergency at the <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, nuclear power plant, the other completed but not operating reactor in the Northeast Though some of the truck sites would slightly exceed federal guidelines of that it should not take more than 15 minutes to set off warnings, the board said the plan by the <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> operators was adequate considering `` the fact that concerned political jurisdictions can reduce alerting and notification times by making sites available for sirens permanently mounted on poles.'' The state of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and its towns in the evacuation zones have refused to cooperate in emergency planning, and <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Jonas </PERSON> said the state would appeal the decision to an appeal board. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> report, an analysis of a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> commission study performed last year of the plant owned by <ORGANIZATION> Long </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lighting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION>, was prepared by an economist with the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION>, which is chaired by Sen. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, D-La. `` His study concludes that the <ORGANIZATION> PSC </ORGANIZATION> report is a biased and unfair comparison of <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> In-Service and the Settlement,'' <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> said in a letter to <LOCATION> Bradford </LOCATION>. `` The study shows that <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION> operation would save three-quarters of a billion dollars in real economic costs over the first 15 years of its life.'' The settlement refers to the pending deal, to be voted on by <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION> shareholders Wednesday, to turn the $ 5.5 billion plant over to the state for $ 1 and assurance of a decade's worth of rate increases of about 5 percent a year. Though fully licensed, the plant has never entered commercial operation. Local and state authorities contend nearby residents could not be evacuated in an emergency. <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> said <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> assigned staff `` to go and find every fault that they could with the PSC-LILCO study.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> staff analysis concludes that <ORGANIZATION> LILCO </ORGANIZATION>'s electric rates with <LOCATION> Shoreham </LOCATION>