<HEAD>Doctors Conducting Trial Of Chinese AIDS Drug</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> announced Tuesday it is investigating doctors in several <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities who are testing an AIDS drug from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> without federal approval. Nine doctors in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> have treated 42 patients with Compound Q, imported from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> with the help of couriers who in some cases bribed <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government officials, doctors said Monday. Three patients showed adverse reactions and one died Saturday. Compound Q is the name AIDS researchers have given to trichosanthin, a protein from the root of a cucumberlike plant that <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> doctors have used to induce abortions and to treat cancer since the third century. Dr. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothman </PERSON>, one of the doctors in the underground testing, said that observations of 15 patients in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> indicated the drug `` appears to be the most effective AIDS medication available or on the horizon.'' `` We would have liked to have done this study formally, and with the approval of the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. `` But one person dies from AIDS every 30 minutes. We felt that as long as we proceeded on a rigorous scientific basis, we would be on very strong ground.'' The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>, under its so-called compassionate use decision, allows individuals to import `` personal use'' quantities of experimental drugs. The supplies must be no more than enough for one individual use for three months. Large-scale importation of unapproved products for commercial use is prohibited. Violating <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> policy on distributing unapproved drugs could result in seizure of the material; cease and desist orders; or, in rare cases, mostly involving for-profit schemes, criminal penalties. The agency said drug testing must be done under its scrutiny. `` We will be investigating this matter, to see just what has occurred,'' said <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> has approved only one drug, AZT, to treat AIDS, and side effects keep many patients from taking it. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> in April approved testing on AIDS patients of GLQ223, a highly purified form of trichosanthin developed at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Genelabs </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Redwood </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. At the time, <ORGANIZATION> Genelabs </ORGANIZATION> warned that AIDS patients should not turn to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> to get the active ingredient because it might have toxic side effects Some AIDS activists charged that the university and <ORGANIZATION> Genelabs </ORGANIZATION> were taking that position to protect an agreement giving their financial backer, the Swiss pharmaceutical company <ORGANIZATION> Sandoz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, exclusive rights to market GLQ223. At least one doctor not involved in the underground testing said the extreme side effects of Compound Q could have contributed to the death Saturday of an AIDS patient at <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zion </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. That was denied by <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON>, co-director of Project Inform, a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> AIDS education group that organized the network of doctors in the underground testing. `` But I want to stress that this is not herbal tea,'' said <PERSON> Delaney </PERSON>. `` This is radical chemotherapy. Some of the patients have had a very rough ride.'' <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> immunologist, Dr. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, who helped set up the study of Compound Q, said the program is at least six months ahead of mainline research on the drug's efficacy and contended he could have dosage recommendations within three months. `` From our tests, we'll have better scientific data in 10 percent of time and 1 percent of the cost it is taking regular science to do the job,'' said <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>. He and his wife, Dr. <PERSON> Vera </PERSON> <PERSON> Byers </PERSON>, designed the trial. `` Our scientific -LRB- procedures -RRB- are very good and rigorous,'' said <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>. `` I resent people calling us underground, illegal or guerilla groups. We're not amateurs. We're first-class doctors.'' <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said lawyers for doctors involved in the program had informed <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> officials earlier this spring of the treatment trial.
