<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House on Tuesday rejected a five-year extension of most-favored-nation trading status for <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, with some members arguing the issue should be left to the president's discretion President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> already has announced he intends to extend the trade preference for another year. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> vote was 242-172 for the legislation, less than the two-thirds necessary to pass a bill under suspension of the rules, a procedure generally reserved for non-controversial bills. During debate, Rep. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> trade subcommittee, said: `` The people of <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> have demonstrated since World War II that they seek and yearn for freedom They're close now. It is time for us to take them off of probation and extend a helping hand.'' Earlier, at a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> hearing, <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamman </PERSON>, deputy assistant secretary of state for <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> affairs, said <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> had made progress in human rights, including free travel and emigration. <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, a communist nation in the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact, will clearly meet the criteria for a new extension of its most-favored-nation status, which presidents have renewed annually over the past decade, he said. In light of that, there is no need for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to direct a five-year extension, he said. Countries in most-favored-nation status are guaranteed the lowest tariffs applicable to their products _ in other words, they will be treated like `` the most favored nation.'' Speaking against the measure on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor, Rep. <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, said the trade benefits should be left to the president to determine, and pointed to the recent Chinese crackdown on the pro-democracy movement as an example of how quickly situations can change. <PERSON> Gilman </PERSON> also hinted that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> might want to make the announcement himself during a trip to <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> in about two weeks. He asked colleagues not to `` pre-empt the president from taking the kinds of steps he would be inclined to do later on this year.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on May 31 announced his intention to extend <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s trade benefit for another year. The president also has generally held out the hope of increased economic aid to East Bloc countries that expand freedoms, and has promised a longer-term extension of most-favored-nation trading status to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> if it passes a liberalized emigration law. Current law bars most-favored-nation status, with its preferential customs duty rates, to communist countries with restrictive emigration policies. Since the ban was imposed in 1974, three nations have been granted waivers: <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.
