<HEAD>Watkins Pledges `New Course' For Safety at Weapons Plants</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs, bgng ``Watkins announcement,'' to include information
on lawsuit filed against Energy Department after 6th graf, bgng ``Waste
production.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> WASHINGTON </LOCATION> _ Energy Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> on Tuesday launched a broad shakeup of nuclear weapons production, pledging to `` chart a new course'' of environmental safeguards and conceding that a key waste storage facility has to be delayed. `` The chickens have finally come home to roost,'' <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said, after `` years of inattention to changing standards and demands regarding the environment, safety and health.'' <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> announced new steps for improving management of the weapons production complex, including 17 major plants or laboratories in 12 states, and for determining the extent to which the facilities are violating state and federal environmental laws. He also said a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> site that was scheduled to open in September as the nation's first permanent dump for waste from the military facilities would not begin receiving waste until sometime in 1990. He said he had no more specific target date. `` We have had a flawed plan'' for opening the Waste Isolation Pilot Plant, he said. Waste production has been reduced, which should allow the production plants to continue operating normally until the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> site opens, he said. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> announcement came as a group of 21 environmental, scientific and church groups sued the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to try to force a broad public review of plans for modernizing the weapons plants. The suit filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> said the department should be compelled to prepare a Programmatic Environmental Impact Statement, a comprehensive analysis of the environmental and health effects of its weapons plant initiatives. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> declined to comment directly on the suit except to say he was committed to ensuring full compliance with all environmental requirements. At his first formal news conference since taking office last March, <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said he was surprised and disappointed to learn of the depth of problems in the weapons program, which has been crippled by mechanical failures and safety problems. `` It has been a nightmare for me to unravel the background sufficient to make a decision,'' he said, adding that he was being forced to act `` on a crisis basis'' because of the urgent need to get key weapons plants running again. Three nuclear reactors at the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Site </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, which are the nation's only source of tritium needed for nuclear warheads, have been shut down for more than a year because of uncertainties about their safety. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said he hoped to announce a reactor restart scheduled in July. In what he called an illustration of the breadth of change he seeks in the weapons program, <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> restart plan would require <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which runs the plant under a federal contract, to devote `` far more resources than our own program coordinator ever demanded'' in the past. He said he was creating environmental `` tiger teams'' to closely examine each weapons plant to assess its compliance with state and federal environmental laws. `` This is a complete review, with my tiger teams moving out to see to what degree we have actually been complying with the intent as well as the letter of the law,'' <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said. The department's increased attention to health and safety issues comes just days after the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> raided the <ORGANIZATION> Rocky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flats </ORGANIZATION> weapons plant in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> in search of evidence of illegal dumping and incineration of hazardous wastes. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> was mildly critical of Justice for refusing to give him any information about its findings at Rocky Flats, which makes plutonium triggers for thermonuclear weapons. He said he wanted to find `` a new way of doing business in these events in the future, if we get into this situation, because I think it's important that we know at once whether there has been any violation of the environment, particularly when radioactivity is involved.'' <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said Rocky Flats illustrated the extent of turmoil in the weapons program. `` I can not certify to you today, or to the public, that we know exactly'' what is contained in radioactive waste stored at Rocky Flats, he said. It will take another four months to `` revalidate'' the contents of the waste, he added. <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> also defended President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s decision to nominate <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Stello </PERSON> as assistant secretary for defense programs, the top job in the weapons program, despite what <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> called `` the potential controversiality'' of the choice. In 1987 a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel conducted a hearing on whether <PERSON> Stello </PERSON>, as executive director for operations of the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, was guilty of improprieties in connection with a commission investigation of the <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Authority </LOCATION>. The probe included the question of whether <PERSON> Stello </PERSON> improperly advised the manager of nuclear power at <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION> on how to respond to a commission inquiry about the readiness of a plant under construction. Stello denied any improprieties. `` If he has some chinks in his armor, so be it,'' <PERSON> Watkins </PERSON> said. `` I have to have somebody in here who wants to serve _ and let me tell you, not many want in on this one _ and has the skills and background to understand from Day One what it means to run a reactor.''
