<HEAD>First Israeli Flight Brings Victims of Armenian Earthquake</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with details of survivors arrival,
quotes, other. CORRECTS figures for survivors, quake homeless. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s national airline made its first direct flight to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on Tuesday and brought 61 survivors of the Armenian earthquake to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for six weeks of treatment. The 49 amputees and 12 victims suffering from multiple fractures, known as the `` crush syndrome,'' came slowly down the ramp. Those able to walk supported themselves with crutches as they limped off, taking their first look at the Jewish state that gathered them in for six weeks of medical treatment. The El Al <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 757 took off for <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, the capital of the Soviet Armenian republic, at 1:30 p.m. and returned to <LOCATION> Ben </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gurion </LOCATION> airport from its historic flight nine hours later. Israeli officials and Archbishop <PERSON> Kerkin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kazanjian </PERSON>, head of the Armenian Church in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, greeted the survivors. <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> immigrants from <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> brought flowers. Health Minister <PERSON> Yaakov </PERSON> <PERSON> Tzur </PERSON> told reporters at the airport, `` This definitely shows we are experiencing a new relationship with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> cut diplomatic relations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> after the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war in a show of solidarity with <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> nations. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> exchanged low-level consular delegations in 1987. The Armenian patients looked confused and smiled uneasily upon their arrival. During the 2 -LCB- - hour flight from <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, many burst into tears recalling the ordeal of the Dec. 7 earthquake that left an estimated 25,000 dead, many thousands injured and 500,000 homeless `` I lost 18 classmates in the earthquake,'' said 17-year-old <PERSON> Egor </PERSON> <PERSON> Khatchaturian </PERSON> of hard-hit <LOCATION> Spitak </LOCATION>. `` They told me a week ago that I was going to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. I feel very well. I hope they will make a prosthesis for me,'' he said. <PERSON> Khatchaturian </PERSON>, who lost his left leg, could not recall what he did after the quake and wept the moment the disaster was mentioned. The youth was traveling alone, his parents back in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. Clutching his crutches, he sat silently in an armchair, dressed in blue sports jacket and blue hat. An Armenian team of two doctors and four nurses accompanied the victims. They will be trained in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to provide the pateints with follow-up treatment. In <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, Armenian officials held a reception for the Israeli group and laid out cheese, meat, vodka and Armenian cognac. On the main table, an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> flag stood beside the red-and-blue Armenian flag. The restaurant band played <PERSON> Hava </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagila </PERSON>, the popular Israeli tune, as officials of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Distribution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> performed a lively dance. `` I hope the time will come when planeloads like yours will land in <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION> without any disaster having prompted their visit,'' said <PERSON> Narine </PERSON> <PERSON> Balayan </PERSON>, the Armenian minister of social affairs who acted as host. The mood grew quieter as survivors emerged one by one from the main building and were carried onto the plane. A bearded Armenian approached and made the sign of cross on their foreheads. `` Go with God,'' somebody muttered. The New-York based <ORGANIZ