<FILEID>AP-NR-06-27-89 1415EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv28   06-27 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 28 ,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Wednesday, June 28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Where Are Automotive Stocks Headed?</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Through marketing ingenuity, incentives, good design, improved quality and sheer persistence, automakers have managed to stretch their selling cycle long beyond its usual lifespan. Now they are faced with another situation: With the delayed but inevitable end of their growth cycle appearing on the horizon, can they manage to maintain their stock prices until the next upturn? Automaking is a cyclical industry, meaning it has at least as many ups and downs as the economy itself. The pattern is as distinct as in real estate: a rising demand, overproduction, big inventories, a downturn and a recovery. It's been a bit different this time. Amid intense competition, the carmakers developed techniques to shift the production mix _ cars vs. trucks, for example _ offer discounts and below-market interest rates, and fine-tune production. In so doing they demonstrated that the cycle can indeed be stretched, if only to a point. Now, with indications it could snap _ July output may be at an annual rate of only 5 million cars, lowest for any month since 1982 _ you might think the appeal of automaker stocks would fall. But it might not. With industry earnings heading for a second-half decline, automotive stocks still remain in many portfolios, one reason being that analysts believe the automakers might be able to do for their stocks what they did for their sales. How do you keep stock prices up? _ By using the money you earned in the good times to buy back your stocks, as <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> are doing, thus tending to maintain the supply-demand ratio _ By maintaining dividends at a rate higher than most blue chips General Motors current dividend yield is 6.6 percent, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s 6.2 percent and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s 4.8 percent. _ By making operations more efficient, thus buffering earnings to some degree against a sales downturn <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> often is cited as the best example of improved operating efficiency. Moreover, it chose to meet demand in the good days by expanding overtime rather than expanding plants. It costs less to reduce overtime than to close a plant. Still another factor, low price-earnings ratios, conceivably could protect share prices. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> sells for six times earnings, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> four and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> five. For the market as a whole, the P-E is in the double digits. Reflecting some of these considerations, The Value Line Investment Survey offers these views of the Big Three automakers on the eve of a sales downturn: GENERAL MOTORS. `` We look for negative quarterly matchups for the remainder of ` 89, and expect the full-year's earnings to decline by about 12 percent ... These shares have impressive total return potential for the three - to five-year term In the meantime, -LRB- they -RRB- provide an above-average yield based on a secure payout ...'' FORD. `` We expect <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> shares to keep pace with the market in the year ahead, protected from most downside risk by a secure dividend that provides an attractive yield.'' <ORGANIZATION> CHRYSLER </ORGANIZATION>. `` Patient investors should keep this stock in mind. Although recent earnings comparisons suggest the stock is only likely to be an average performer in the year ahead, we project sharply improved earnings for the company by 1992-1994. If it turns out that way, the major automakers may have succeeded not just in muting the ups and downs of the car market but of the stock market too.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday, June 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890627-0214 </DOCNO>
