<HEAD>For Release Tues AMs, July 4, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Arab Day Labor Is Controversial Issue in Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PETAH TIKVA, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A plan to keep Palestinian day laborers in a fenced-in compound while they wait to be hired in <ORGANIZATION> Petah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tikva </ORGANIZATION> has fueled debate over the wisdom and morality of using Arabs to work in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Critics of restrictions on <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> laborers say the practice is similar to what <PERSON> Nazis </PERSON> did to Jews in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, but proponents maintain that after 18 months of a violent <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> uprising in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, restrictions are necessary for safety and security. Caught in the middle are the Arabs, who usually work as construction laborers, street cleaners, garbage collectors and at other menial jobs, and their employers, who pay them about half what <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> workers would have to be paid. In the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> settlement of Ariel, officials backed down from a plan to make the Arabs wear tags labeling them `` alien workers'' after critics compared them to the yellow Stars of <PERSON> David </PERSON> that Jews were forced to wear in <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. When the town council in <ORGANIZATION> Petah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tikva </ORGANIZATION>, a city of 150,000 six miles east of <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>, approved the holding area for Arab workers in May, some Israeli newspapers said it amounted to a `` temporary prison.'' The original plan called for a fenced-in holding pen where <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> workers would be required to show their identity cards and wait to be hired. But after the public outcry, the town decided to do away with plans for the fence and a legal requirement that workers wait inside. Instead, a metal-frame shelter with a green plastic roof was erected over three park benches; a portable toilet was put up nearby. On one recent day, the shelter was empty and several <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> workers waited at a corner about 100 yards away. `` People are afraid to go to the shelter,'' said one of the workers, identifying himself as only as <PERSON> Faisal </PERSON>. `` They are afraid of the police or of citizens here who might plant bombs or shoot guns at us.'' <PERSON> Avraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Oren </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Petah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tikva </ORGANIZATION> town council member who opposes the shelter, said it would probably never be used because of the controversy it has caused. `` This idea that it is possible to put people in pens is like segregation of the races,'' he said. But council spokesman <PERSON> Shuki </PERSON> <PERSON> Yelin </PERSON> defended the shelter, saying it was meant to ease fears by Jewish parents that their children might be attacked by <PERSON> Arabs </PERSON> on the streets. `` We built it because ... many Jewish citizens protested and sent petitions, saying they are suffering because of the presence of the Arabs near their houses,'' <PERSON> Yelin </PERSON> said. `` It's not racist. We know we are criticized, but it's not a jail. We do n't force them to go. It's an open place.'' Similarly expressed fears have been behind other moves to restrict <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> workers. Mayor <PERSON> Zvi </PERSON> <PERSON> Zilker </PERSON> of the southern Israeli town of <LOCATION> Ashdod </LOCATION> temporarily barred all Palestinian laborers recently after a soldier was killed nearby and another disappeared and was believed kidnapped. Police said they suspected Palestinians from the <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> in both cases. After the attacks on soldiers, the Israeli government also began requiring <PERSON> Gaza </PERSON> <PERSON> Arabs </PERSON> to obtain new work permits and restricting those with records of crime or security offenses. But right-wing calls for barring all Arab workers from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> have brought an outcry from employers who depend on them. The issue has opened up a debate that touches not only <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s economy but also many Israelis' vision of their country as a bulwark of Jewish morality that does not condone exploiting the Arabs Professor <PERSON> Ehpraim </PERSON> <PERSON> Yuchtman-Yaar </PERSON>, a social psychologist at <ORGANIZATION> Tel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviv </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, says Israelis are torn between dependence on Arab workers and guilt over their treatment. `` People recognize the labor is vital for the Israeli economy,'' he said. `` They are doing low-status jobs that Israelis prefer not to do. But morally, many Israelis feel the Arabs should be treated equally to Jewish workers. ... Because they are not, it is exploitation and should be denounced.'' <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Semyonov </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Tel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviv </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> sociologist, says the segregation of Arabs is being fostered by a curious alliance between right-wing Israelis and traditionalists who see the use of <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> labor crushing their dream of an <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> built by Jews. `` People on both ends of the political spectrum are against depending on Arabs _ one out of antagonism, the other for humanistic or moral reasons,'' <PERSON> Semyonov </PERSON> said.
