<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--Yehoshua Adv07-09-1stLd-Writethru bcottonfuturesweretrading
06-27 1009</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Yehoshua, Adv 07-09 - 1st Ld-Writethru, b0822,1027</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv07</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, July 7-9 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: The Importance of Myth for Israeli Writers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 1st graf to correct spelling of Israel.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Early in 1988, a letter composed by four Israeli writers appeared in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> urging American Jews to speak out against <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s violent crackdown of <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> protesters in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. One of the writers was A.B. <PERSON> Yehoshua </PERSON>, whose novels include `` A Late Divorce'' and the recently released `` Five Seasons'' -LRB- Doubleday, $ 19.95 -RRB-. <PERSON> Yehoshua </PERSON>, <PERSON> Amos </PERSON> <PERSON> Oz </PERSON>, <PERSON> Yehuda </PERSON> <PERSON> Amichai </PERSON> and other Israeli writers uphold a tradition of active participation in their country's politics. Zionism, or Jewish statehood, they note, was created by a writer _ <PERSON> Theodor </PERSON> <PERSON> Herzl </PERSON>. `` The main figures of the first Zionist congress were writers,'' said <PERSON> Yehoshua </PERSON>, professor of literature at <ORGANIZATION> Haifa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` By their imagination they understood what was going to happen to the Jewish people.'' <PERSON> Avraham </PERSON> <PERSON> Bulli </PERSON> <PERSON> Yehoshua </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> in 1936 at a time when the city was part of British-controlled <LOCATION> Palestine </LOCATION>. When he was 12 years old, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> was granted independence and won a fierce war with Arabs for possession of the land. `` I remember always sitting under the shelters and being without food. I remember the fighting, the shelling, the bullets. I was worried about my father, who was working in the secret service, listening to the Arabs' telephone calls,'' he said. He did n't originally want to be a writer, dreaming instead about a legal career. But as a teen-ager, <PERSON> Yehoshua </PERSON> joined a youth group and impressed his peers with humorous pieces about local events. He continued to write while serving in the army. `` I was writing about things in the unit _ creating absurd situations in a very fantastic kind of style, describing what was inside the camp. This was the idea: absurd stories, fantastic stories.'' His first published work, a short story about a dying man, was also an absurdist piece. `` He's still alive but the old woman decides to bury him alive, to get rid of him,'' <PERSON> Yehoshua </PERSON> said about the work. `` The neighbors are participating in this live burial, and I'm writing about how this can be achieved.'' <PERSON> Yehoshua </PERSON> soon became influenced by the works of <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Faulkner </PERSON>, admiring the great Southern writer's stream-of-consciousness prose and blending of myth and reality. The use of myth is important for an Israeli writer. `` We do n't have a long history as an independent country so you have to relate yourself to some myth,'' <PERSON> Yehoshua </PERSON> said `` <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has changed so radically it's unbelieveable.'' A self-described `` dove'' who favors talks between <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> and eventual <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> self-determination, recalled a short story he had written in 1962: `` A student is sent to a forest because he did n't finish his studies and his friends are advising him to finish his thesis. So he's sent to a forest. There's an Arab in the distance planning to set fire to the forest because it was built on his village. Finally, the forest is set on fire. `` In 1962, it was an indication that the Palestinian problem was being repressed. The Palestinian problem has been coming, expecially in the last year. It's a sign that the Israelis have to realize the limits of Zionism.'' Politics are not mentioned directly in `` Five Seasons,'' which chronicles the difficulties of a middle-aged government bureaucrat, <PERSON> Molkho </PERSON>, in adjusting to the death of his wife, who succumbs to cancer at the start of the novel. <PERSON> Molkho </PERSON> anxiously seeks companionship, flying to <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> for a weekend with the legal adviser from work, and spending time with the wife of his old youth group counselor, who has encouraged the meeting. But <PERSON> Molkho </PERSON> is unable to connect with either woman, as the grief over his late wife makes him alternately abrupt and distant, incapable of understanding their feelings. `` My point in this book is that this was the year <PERSON> Molkho </PERSON> thinks he'll be free,'' <PERSON> Yehoshua </PERSON> said. `` Without believing in ghosts he interiorizes his wife in such a way that she's still alive after her death. And this is the way he has to struggle until then he's liberated. Where `` A Late Divorce'' showed <PERSON> Faulkner </PERSON>'s unmistakable influence, <PERSON> Yehoshua </PERSON>'s writing in `` Five Seasons'' is in keeping with his main character: restrained, introverted and obsessed with minor details. `` It had to be much more subtle,'' the author said. `` When you are writing stream-of-consciousness, everything has to get out. With this, there's what you say and what you do n't say. There's a gap between the two. In a way, I was returning to the style of my short stories.'' In one passage, <PERSON> Yehoshua </PERSON> describes <PERSON> Molkho </PERSON>'s thoughts while attending a dinner party given by the legal adviser: `` The conversation rambled intimately. Though he had prepared a few subjects to talk about, especially several of a legal nature, he saw at once that he need n't make the effort, for everyone appeared harmoniously acquainted and he, it seemed, was passed back and forth among them in a discreet and unaffected fashion. `` Afraid of being suspected of some organic problem if he went to the toilet too soon, he sat with his legs together to ease the pressure on his bladder while one by one the men came up to him, introducing themselves once again ...'' <PERSON> Yehoshua </PERSON> is a strong critic of the diaspora, the dispersion of Jews around the world, stating that the failure of Jewish people to return to their homeland presents a greater threat than the Arabs to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s national security. Yet in the final chapter of `` Five Seasons,'' <PERSON> Molkho </PERSON> helps an unhappy Russian-born girl return to her home country. `` It was a healthy thing for her to do,'' <PERSON> Yehoshua </PERSON> explained. `` I do n't tell you to stay. You have to feel natural. By understanding the Russian's feelings, <PERSON> Molkho </PERSON> can better understand himself and demonstrate his belonging to the country.''
</TEXT>
