<FIRST>r f PM-BoeingSST Bjt   06-27 0824</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing SST, Bjt,0846</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Boeing Exploring New SST, But Foresees Many Problems</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENTON, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new generation of supersonic jetliners might be built, but only if manufacturers can conquer the immense environmental, technical and economic problems of a plane that would fly at twice the speed of sound while costing twice as much as a 747, a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> official says. `` This is <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> dreaming,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON>, manager of High-Speed Commercial Transport studies for <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>. `` But it's our job in new airplane development to protect the future of the company. About 70 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> employees has been looking at whether a new supersonic transport could be flying within the next 20 years. The early outlook, <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> said Monday, is that it could be done, but not easily. <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> said that <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> _ the only other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> maker of commercial jets _ the Europeans and the Japanese also have looked at new-generation SSTs, and appear to have reached similar conclusions. `` We and <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> have been working on parallel paths,'' said <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Takahashi </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> each received $ 4.5 million from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> for a two-year study on the feasibility of a new SST Both companies decided to continue the research after the study ended last fall. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> declined to say how much it has spent so far. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> pinned a lot of hopes and a lot of money in the late 1960s on building an SST. When the government canceled the program over environmental concerns, it contributed to the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> slump that plunged <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, its headquarters city, into hard times in the early 1970s. Because of this, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> executives have said they are wary of committing the hundreds of millions of dollars it would take to build a new SST. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Albrecht </PERSON>, executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airplanes </ORGANIZATION> division, has said that while the Concorde SST has been successful as a premium trans-Atlantic service, he doubts anyone would build _ nor would airlines buy _ a plane that must command a much higher ticket price to serve a niche market. The Anglo-French Concorde began flying passengers in 1976. Only about a dozen of the sleek jets now fly, operated by <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> France </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, and are severely limited in routes because of noisy engines and ear-rattling sonic boom resulting from it flying about twice the speed of sound. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> is studying a plane capable of flying 1.8 to 2.5 times the speed of sound, or roughly 1,330 to 1,850 mph. That would permit it to fly from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> in 4 hours 20 minutes, compared with the 10 hours, 20 minutes a non-stop subsonic flight takes today. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> doubts a faster plane would be practical, because it would require new fuels such as liquid natural gas or liquid hydrogen, and special airport facilities, <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> said. Further, a plane that could fly 2,500 mph or better would have scant time at cruising speed on a 5,000-mile trans-Pacific flight. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s four-engine <ORGANIZATION> HSCT </ORGANIZATION>, a long, languid curve in profile, is envisioned to be about 293 feet long, 60 feet longer than a 747-400 jumbo jet, with a wingspan of just 142 feet, or 70 feet less than the 747-400. It would haul 200 to 300 passengers about 5,000 nautical miles non-stop. The Concorde is about 204 feet long with an 84-foot wingspan and carries 100 to 128 passengers 3,360 nautical miles non-stop. By using engine noise suppressors, <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> planners think their <ORGANIZATION> HSCT </ORGANIZATION> could meet the government's strict new standards for airport noise. Sonic boom is another matter. `` We saw no way and still see no way we could reduce sonic boom to acceptable levels over land,'' <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> said. Another environmental worry is possible damage to the ozone layer. By limiting the plane to under <ORGANIZATION> Mach </ORGANIZATION> 3, or three times the speed of sound, it could still fly below the ozone layer, in the troposphere, where engine emissions should be dispersed, <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> HSCT </ORGANIZATION> would require some yet-to-be developed technology, especially in lightweight composite materials. Just as critical is making the plane economical to fly, he said. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> estimates air traffic in 2015 will be about 1.9 million passenger miles per day, roughly twice what it is now. About a third of all passengers would be on routes that could be served by an <ORGANIZATION> HSCT </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> said. The problem, he said, is that to compete, an <ORGANIZATION> HSCT </ORGANIZATION> has to offer a ticket price roughly the same as the newer and cheaper-to-operate long-range widebody jets. That could be tough, he said, for a plane that probably would cost twice as much as a 747-400, which sells for about $ 125 million. In <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION>'s market research, `` even an optimistic look says that if you were to increase the ticket prices by as much as 20 percent, we'd lose over half the market,'' he said.
