<FIRST>r f PM-Time Bjt   06-27 0678</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time, Bjt,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Rejects Sweetened Paramount Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has rejected <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 12.2 billion takeover bid, noting that the sweetened offer is subject to the same unresolved conditions as <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s earlier $ 10.7 billion proposal. Time's board, which turned down the revised $ 200-a-share bid Monday, also called the offer financially inadequate, and the media giant restated its intention to pursue a $ 14 billion tender offer of its own for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` The <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> offer remains as highly conditional and conjectural as it was when <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> started it nearly three weeks ago,'' Time said in a statement Monday. Paramount has conditioned its buyout on being able to obtain financing for the deal _ which it did not accomplish while its earlier $ 175-a-share bid was on the table _ and on obtaining the rights to operate about 800 cable television systems Time owns. The bid is also contingent upon the termination of Time's merger agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>. Time, which has focused on these conditions in its campaign against <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>, claims they will prevent the Paramount bid from being completed and has urged its shareholders not to be tempted by the size of the offer. `` It's not just the question of price,'' Time Vice Chairman <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said in a telephone interview Monday. Paramount was undaunted by the latest rejection. `` We will continue to pursue our acquisition of Time in a calm, studied and deliberate manner,'' it said in a statement. Time announced its rejection of the Paramount bid after the close of trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Time stock seesawed in nervous trading as investors awaited the board's response, rising as high as $ 172.25 a share before closing at $ 164 a share, down $ 1.87 -LCB- from Friday's close. Securities analysts had expected Time to reject any sweetened bid. However, observers said they did not expect <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> to raise its offer again and <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> indicated the company expected the takeover struggle to be resolved in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chancery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Court </LOCATION>, where Paramount has sued to block Time's planned $ 70-a-share buyout of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>. A key issue before the court in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> _ where all three companies are incorporated _ is whether <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> put itself up for sale, thereby opening itself up to the bid from <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>, when it announced its merger agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> in March. Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> originally agreed to merge in a stock-for-stock transaction but revised their merger agreement to provide for <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s tender offer after Paramount announced its first bid on June 6 Paramount contends that Time's tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> was begun solely as a defense against the Paramount bid. `` I just believe that when the court looks at these issues, that there's a fairly persuasive case that we have a transaction that has not been done defensively ...'' <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> said. `` It's something we've studied for so long. When they announced their plans to merge, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> said they had been negotiating over two years. Time stated that its board base