<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar was mixed in quiet, early European trading today, and foreign currency dealers said the market was waiting for cues from economic news to be released this week. Gold prices fell. `` The dollar is completely flat today,'' said one trader in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. He said investors were uncertain about where to go and were waiting for Thursday's release of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> leading economic indicators and for the outcome of the West German central bank's policy meeting the same day. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 1.05 yen to a closing 141.23 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted higher at 141.35 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's prices, included: 1.9558 West German marks, up from 1.9552; 1.6840 Swiss francs, unchanged; 6.6343 French francs, down from 6.6380; 2.2045 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2003; 1,415.55 Italian lire, up from 1,414.00; and 1.1943 Canadian dollars, up from 1.19405 The dollar fell slightly against the British pound in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. It cost $ 1.5495 to buy one pound, compared with $ 1.5450 late Monday. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 374.30 a troy ounce, compared with late Monday's $ 375.25. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 373.55. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 373.85, down from $ 374.25 late Monday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 1.15 to close at a bid of $ 375.11. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 5.29 a troy ounce, down from Monday's $ 5.33.
