<HEAD>Dollar Rises, Stocks Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rose sharply against the Japanese yen today, while the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s main index plunged. The dollar closed at 141.23 yen, up 1.05 yen from Monday's close of 140.18 yen. It opened at 141.15 yen and fluctuated between 140.90 yen and 141.30 yen. The dollar had fallen 4.77 yen in three trading days before today's rebound. <PERSON> Mitsuhiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Kinugasa </PERSON>, a trader at <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, said the rebound mainly reflected position adjustments. `` Nothing happened today,'' he added. `` There were no buying incentives, there were no releases of major economic indicators this week, there was no central bank intervention _ nothing.'' <PERSON> Kinugasa </PERSON> said, `` The yen's sharp rebound last week has come to a halt, and the majority of investors are now avoiding major moves until they find a new trend in the market.'' The dollar had risen to a nearly two-year high closing of 151.30 on June 15 before heading back down. On the stock market, the 225-issue <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> lost 156.61 points, or 0.47 percent, closing at 33,469.21. The market's main barometer had gained 95.11 points Monday <PERSON> Masahiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Umemori </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, said the index fell mainly because of the yen's decline against the dollar and the governing <ORGANIZATION> Liberal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s loss in a parliamentary by-election on Sunday. `` Japanese investors were reluctant to buy issues because of uncertainties over the direction of the foreign exchange and pessimism over performance in the upper house election,'' he said. Elections for half the seats in the upper house are scheduled for July 23. Other dealers said speculative investors sold spot issues for arbitrage deals between the spot and the futures markets, prompting the Nikkei's fall in the afternoon session. Trading was thin, with first section volume estimated at 500 million shares, up from Monday's 430 million.
