<HEAD>EEC Leaders Compromise on Plan to Unite Their Economies</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Thatcher, Mitterrand, Kohl comments;
no pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> leaders today agreed on a compromise plan for gradually unifying their economies after <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> succeeded in blocking attempts to create a single currency and a central bank. `` We have conceded nothing at all,'' <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> said at the end of a two-day summit. However, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which were aligned against <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in the dispute over broad plans to unify the economies, also declared themselves pleased with the compromise pact. Closer monetary union is part of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s drive toward December 1992, when the member nations will drop trade barriers to form a single market. West German Chancellor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> said the agreement at the end of a two-day <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> summit was a `` superb result. `` The foundation has been laid for a development that brings the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> further together and brings political union one step nearer,'' <PERSON> Kohl </PERSON> told reporters. The 12 <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> leaders have been divided over how far and how fast to go toward closer economic and monetary union as part of the establishment of a single Europe-wide market in 1992. In a final communique, the leaders endorsed only part of a sweeping plan for monetary union drawn up by <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Delors </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s executive body, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. The communique avoided setting any deadline on the more controversial aspects of the plan: creating a single currency and a central bank. But it did provide for the calling of the intergovernmental conference on those proposals, something Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> had sought to avoid. French President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> said he would call an intergovernmental conference after next year. The conference can be called by a simple majority, but once there any member nation could then veto the changes. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> also agreed in principle to link the pound to the exchange rate mechanism that aligns the value of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s major currencies. But Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> hedged the move, which she has long resisted, with strict conditions. These included that <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s 8.3 percent inflation must drop to near the 4.5 percent average in the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> and that arrangements for the single market must be complete. Besides <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, some smaller <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> nations, including <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>, have also expressed reservations about the <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> plan. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> clashed repeatedly during the summit behind closed doors, officials reported, and jibed publicly at each other afterward. Each claimed that it was the other who was the other who had been most isolated at the conference. `` It was not me who was isolated,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>. `` It was President <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> agreed with a French radio interviewer that Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> was the `` brake'' on <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. She retorted at a news conference, `` Its a bit rich, is n't it _ someone who has not got freedom of capital movement ... calling me a brake on <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. He has scarcely got into the car.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, adopting a more conciliatory manner than usual at this summit, agreed Monday to support in principle the linking of the British pound to a system that aligns the major <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> currencies. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> rejects full monetary integration as surrendering to the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> national policy-making powers on budgetary and other financial matters. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> conference said he was `` very satisfied'' with the summit. Asked if he was angry about Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s resistance to the <PERSON> Delors </PERSON> plan, which he strongly favored, he said, `` One should not confuse a certain firmness with anger.'' He added smiling, `` I am used to her ... she's very nice.''
