<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> May </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> today said it is exploring the possibility of selling its <ORGANIZATION> Caldor </ORGANIZATION> and Venture subsidiaries, the company's discount segment. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON>, May chairman and chief executive officer, said the company has asked the investment banking firm <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to look into the possible sales `` The divestiture of <ORGANIZATION> Caldor </ORGANIZATION> and Venture will allow May to focus on the operations and expansion of our higher-return and faster-growing businesses, department stores and specialty shoe stores,'' <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON> said that with the additions last year of <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s and <ORGANIZATION> Filene </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>, two department store chains, May's 14 department store divisions produced sales of $ 7.5 billion and operating earnings of $ 802 million. Volume Shoe's sales were $ 1.1 billion with operating earnings of $ 138 million. <ORGANIZATION> Caldor </ORGANIZATION>'s sales for 1988 came to $ 1.6 billion with earnings of $ 50 million and Venture's sales amounted to $ 1.3 billion with earnings of $ 81 million. May said it anticipates using a significant portion of any proceeds from the divestiture to buy back its stock, depending on market conditions and other factors. The company said it would use the balance of any proceeds for general corporate purposes, including expansion of its department store and specialty shoe businesses. May is one of the largest retailers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATI