<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Trade     06-27 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Trade,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Improves Dramatically</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 6 percent increase in exports helped <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s merchandise trade deficit narrow more sharply than expected to 1.72 billion pounds in May, the government said Tuesday The figures provided some evidence that the government's strategy of cooling the economy with high interest rates was working. The numbers raised hopes that interest rates, which stand at 14 percent, wo n't be pushed higher again. The British pound and stock prices rose after the figures were announced. The seasonally adjusted deficit compared with a shortfall of 2.16 billion pounds, or $ 3.35 billion, in April, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> said. The current account deficit shrank to 1.32 billion pounds from 1.76 billion pounds. The current account includes invisible trade such as overseas investment earnings. Invisible trade was estimated to be in surplus by 400 million pounds. The figures compared with market expectations of a merchandise trade gap of 2.1 billion pounds and a current account deficit of 1.6 billion pounds. Exports totaled 7.58 billion pounds, up from 7.14 billion pounds. The department attributed 243 million pounds of the rise to aircraft deals. Imports were flat at 9.3 billion pounds. Since the beginning of 1989, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s merchandise trade deficit has grown to 9.74 billion pounds compared with a deficit of 7.06 billion pounds a year earlier.
</TEXT>
