<HEAD>Baker Proposes Asian Trade Alliance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> has proposed establishing an Asian trade alliance involving the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the emerging economic powers of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rim </LOCATION>. Although he did n't provide a detailed blueprint, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> told a black-tie dinner of the <ORGANIZATION> Asia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit group, late Monday his plan would focus on coordinating the region's trade and economic policies. He said the new alliance should also focus on other issues ranging from cultural affairs to the environment. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said he plans to seek input on the plan during a trip to <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> that starts July 3. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> will stop in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> to help plan multinational economic aid for the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION>, he will attend the annual meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, an economic organization of <LOCATION> Brunei </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>. Intra-Asian trade last year totaled nearly $ 200 billion, reflecting the rapid pace of <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rim </LOCATION> economic integration, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` Yet unlike <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' he said, `` there are inadequate regional mechanisms to deal with the effects of interdependence.'' <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s new foreign minister, <PERSON> Hiroshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitsuzuka </PERSON>, who met with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> earlier Monday, spoke at the <ORGANIZATION> Asia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> dinner before <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>. He stressed the need for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> `` to maintain a strong political, economic and military presence and commitment to the region.'' If a <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rim </LOCATION> group could be established it would ensure the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> a stronger role in the region and provide a forum for working out nagging trade problems. On <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> defended <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s cautious response to the brutal crackdown of pro-democracy demonstrators, saying it would be a mistake to dismantle the relationship the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> built up over two decades with the Communist government in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>.
