<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Orders Miners to End Wildcat Strikes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: COMBINES urgent series. CORRECTS Joel to Joe in 4th graf pvs
bg'ng, UMW national ...; minor editing throughout; No pickup; Also moved
on general newswires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN GILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge today ordered nearly 43,000 coal miners in nine states to end a wildcat strike and go back to work. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Knapp </PERSON> issued the indefinite restraining order against the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> at the request of the National Labor Relations Board. The nearly 43,000 miners walked out in support of 1,900 <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> members who have been on strike against <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> since April 5. UMW Vice President <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Corcoran </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> did not immediately return a telephone call. Miners have ignored previous restraining orders and remained off the job. <PERSON> Knapp </PERSON> said union officials must report to the <ORGANIZATION> NLRB </ORGANIZATION> within 10 days on what steps they have taken to meet the court order. The judge could have restricted the back-to-work order to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and parts of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, but instead made it nationwide, ordering that it apply to all coal companies with whom the <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> has contracts. About 1,600 <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> miners in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> went on strike against <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> on April 5 after working 14 months without a contract. They were joined by 300 <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> miners in <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> earlier this month. That strike spurred wildcat sympathy walkouts beginning June 12 in <LOCATION> Appalachia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. At one point, 46,000 miners in <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> were off the job. Missouri's miners went back to work on Monday Most of the nation's union miners began their two-week vacations this week, and the coal fields have been relatively quiet since the weekend. On Monday, a second attempt by Gov. <PERSON> Gaston </PERSON> <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON> to mediate in the 11-week-old <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> walkout fell short when <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> declined to say whether he would meet with <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Trumka </PERSON>. <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON> had invited <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> and <PERSON> Trumka </PERSON> last week to meet at the governor's mansion. But <PERSON> Caperton </PERSON> attached several conditions unacceptable to <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>, including asking that <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> not use other coal companies to fill its orders and that other companies suspend any lawsuits against the <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> over the strikes. The governor's latest offer contained no conditions.
