<FIRST>s f BC-ScamCapitals Adv02   06-27 1164</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Scam Capitals, Adv 02,1196</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sun, Surf and Scams in Southern California and South Florida</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There are more than balmy breezes blowing from the south. Hundreds of sweet-talking scam operators are working the telephones to con victims out of a few hundred dollars or, in some cases, their life savings. Investigators estimate 90 percent of all the major `` boiler room'' telemarketing schemes in the nation are based in either <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, with affluent <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, dethroning <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> several years ago as the country's scam capital. The pitches are limited only by the imagination _ from oil wells to medical breakthroughs; worm ranches to low-cost precious metals _ and rope in nearly $ 1 billion annually, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Officials say the best salesmen can mold a lump of truth into a monument of credibility and disguise a sham as a once-in-a-lifetime deal. `` These boiler room guys like life in the fast lane: the yachts, the fancy cars, the sunshine,'' said <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Neal </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Broward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Crime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION> based in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> offer the kind of lifestyle they want.'' Scam artists also like southern climes for their transient populations and ready pools of pitchmen. `` Some of the ads they run specifically target struggling actors or musicians,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Katz </PERSON>, coordinator of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fraud </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> based in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` In an way, it's like an acting job They try to give the pitch as sincerely and convincingly as possible. Too many times it works.'' Tougher state laws and more aggressive enforcement have driven many boiler room operators from the <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> area, but <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> estimates about 80 large telemarketing fraud operations still carry on from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Katz </PERSON> said at least 150 boiler rooms have staked out <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, with most centered around <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>. The boiler room's ability to survive is partially due to lack of coordination betwen federal and state law enforcement agencies and the con artists' nomadic instincts, say investigators. `` When the law gets too close, they pack up shop and begin again,'' said Deputy State Attorney <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON>, a boiler room specialist based in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>. The first telephone scams began in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> in the 1920s, when salesmen would pitch mosquito-infested swampland as prime property. The boiler rooms _ so called for their typically spartan surroundings _ did not flourish again until the 1970s. This time, sure-bet oil and gas fields and inexpensive gems and gold dominated the pitches, said <PERSON> Neal </PERSON>. One of <PERSON> Neal </PERSON>'s favorite souvenirs from the early'80s heyday of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> boiler rooms is a piece of wood carved and painted to resemble a gold bar. It was found with others in the vaults of <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bullion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, one of the boldest and most notorious fraud scams on record. From unusually swank offices in a <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION> skyscraper topped with the IGBE logo, principals <PERSON> William </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Alderdice </PERSON> reportedly made $ 75 million on fraudulent sales of gold, silver and platinum to 13,000 investors, many reassured by IGBE ads in the Wall Street Journal. Some IGBE salesmen earned $ 8,000 a week and the Alderdices were known to toss $ 100 bills from their stretch limousine and watch folks scramble for the cash. <PERSON> Neal </PERSON>'s successful prosecution of IGBE in 1985 was the first major boiler room case in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and is credited with beginning the crackdown that drove many to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Alderdice </PERSON> was hacked to death by his chauffeur before the trial began and his brother received a 10-year federal and a six-year state sentence. `` We are an equal opportunity agency. We prosecute anyone. We have doctors, lawyers and Indian chiefs,'' <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> said, pointing to a photo of <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kabrahrah </PERSON>, a former Comanche tribal leader who became involved in a $ 40 million scam to sell rights to non-producing natural gas wells in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>. And the victims _ known as mooches or mullets in boiler-room parlance _ are just as varied. `` It's no longer just the retirees getting burned. Yuppies with money to spend are becoming the new targets,'' said <PERSON> Neal </PERSON>. Some emerging scams include bogus job search agencies, travel club rip-offs and touting low-priced `` penny'' stocks, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fraud </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telemarketing </ORGANIZATION>, a watchdog group. <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> has also noticed organized crime taking an interest in boiler rooms. In April, the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> charged the nation's largest penny stock dealer, <ORGANIZATION> Stuart-James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc. of <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, with defrauding clients at its <LOCATION> Boca </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Raton </LOCATION> office by making exaggerated claims about companies `` A good boiler room salesman is like a chameleon,'' said <PERSON> Neal </PERSON>. `` If you are religious, suddenly they are born-again. If you have kids, they are suddenly the concerned parent. They tell you what you want to hear.'' In <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, scams involving vitamins and prize contests are hot, say investigators. The boiler rooms hook customers with a postcard saying they have won a valuable prize _ sometimes cash, a car or jewelry. The catch is that the customers must also purchase a supply of vitamins or some other item. Often the vitamins or prize are never delivered or they are grossly inferior to the product described by the `` yaks,'' or boiler room salesmen. Yet local agencies are often slow to crack down, said <PERSON> Katz </PERSON>. `` The cops here are dealing with drug traffic, gang violence and all sorts of other things,'' said <PERSON> Katz </PERSON>, whose office has prosecuted 300 people since 1986. Some areas, such as <LOCATION> Clark </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, have discouraged boiler rooms by requiring costly bonds for each company and every employee of a telemarking firm. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> began registration of telemarketing firms in January 1987, and operators face a maximum penalty of one year in prison and a $ 10,000 fine for failing to comply. <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> adopted tough boiler-room laws in October 1986, including making schemes involving more than $ 50,000 in losses a first-degree felony punishable by up to 30 years in prison. In 1987, <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> was convicted of swindling $ 11 million from 4,000 investors in his <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Precious </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metals </ORGANIZATION> firm and was sentenced to 585 years in prison, believed to be the longest white-collar crime sentence. <PERSON> Neal </PERSON> has one letter he ca n't forget. It came in early 1987 from <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaminsky </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Hazleton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, who lost $ 70,000 in mostly borrowed money in the United Precious Metals scam. `` I feel foolish and unable to make decisions. I always feel as though I will make another devastating mistake,'' wrote <PERSON> Kaminsky </PERSON>. `` These letters tear me up,'' said <PERSON> Neal </PERSON>. `` When a guy robs you on the street at least he is up front and only takes what is in your pocket. With telemarketing scams, they do n't just take what's in your pocket, but everything else you own. You can make more money, but it's the emotional impact you may never recover from.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday July 2</NOTE>
