<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet3pm     06-27 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0440</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices moved higher today, rebounding from a round of selling Monday as interest rates declined in the bond market. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 21.62 to 2,533.00 at 3 p.m. on Wall Street. Gainers outnumbered losers by almost 2 to 1 in nationwide trading of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> Exchange-listed stocks, with 934 up, 506 down and 516 unchanged. Volume on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> totaled 143.09 million shares with one hour to go. Traders said the gains indicated the impact of Monday's more than 20-point decline in the Dow industrials had waned. Many traders cashed in profits Monday after the market rallied last week, pushing the Dow industrials up more than 45 points. Declining interest rates in the bond market helped propel stocks higher, analysts said. Today's gains also were attributed to institutions attempting to complete their second-quarter trading ahead of the July 4 weekend to prepare midyear portfolio reports for clients. `` I think the market is finding a trading range here,'' said <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Peroni </PERSON>, director of technical research for <ORGANIZATION> Janney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` There seems to be good buying interest today.'' The stock market advanced last week to new post-crash highs amid gathering signs of a slowing economy, which were seen as indicators that inflation would not accelerate. That would be positive news for corporate earnings. <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> was up 7 ~ to 147 -LRB- on unconfirmed reports that <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> was part of a group that had acquired a stake in the company, parent of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZA