<HEAD>Wheat Leads Rise In Crop Futures, Soviet Buying Cited</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The wheat market led grain and soybean futures prices to a sharply higher close Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, reflecting ideas that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is seeking to buy more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat. The rally drove wheat futures to their highest level since mid-May and erased most of Monday's steep losses in the corn, soybean and oat markets. Unlike the other grains, wheat futures had risen Monday on signs that the Soviets had bought up to 500,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat at market prices, an indication that they had an immediate need for the grain. Tuesday's rally was fueled by speculation that the Soviets would be back for more wheat and by reports of rain-induced harvest delays in the central and southern states where soft red winter wheat _ the variety reportedly sought by the Soviets _ is grown. `` There are also a lot of quality concerns in the soft red wheat, which makes large-scale buying particularly bullish,'' said <PERSON> Katharina </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmer </PERSON>, a grain-market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. At the close of trading, wheat was -LCB- cent to 10 \ cents higher with the contract for delivery in July at $ 4.12 a bushel; corn was 3 -LCB- cents to 4 -RCB- cents higher with July at $ 2.62 -LCB- a bushel; oats were 4 -RCB- cents to 5 -LCB- cents higher with July at $ 1.53 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 4 cents to 13 -LCB- cents higher with July at $ 7.40 a bushel
