<HEAD>Six-Year-Old Airline Typifies Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By INGER SANDAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thirty years ago, <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> left an accounting job at a steel company for one in the airline industry that offered $ 15 more a month. Today, he operates the nation's 10th-largest airline <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> is a prototype of successful companies in the 1980s _ slick, opportunistic, oriented to employees' needs. A child of deregulation, the 6-year-old airline made $ 10 million last quarter while some other carriers waded in red ink. It projects a $ 30 million profit this year. While metal fatigue made headlines last year in the wake of fatal accidents, <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> fielded a fleet of 74 aircraft, mostly <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s and 757s, averaging only 5.6 years old. `` We have a very good market niche ... and we've always been adequately financed and our people are extremely productive,'' <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> says. `` You have to have all these elements in place or you can not deal with the significantly competitive atmosphere that we have.'' <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> recently failed in its most ambitious undertaking _ an attempt to buy <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' Northeast shuttle out from under developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> _ despite offering $ 50 million more than <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON>, the 52-year-old chairman and chief executive whose swashbuckling image is stamped on his airline, did n't get where he is by putting his eggs in one basket. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> has applied for federal approval to start flights to <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> and is constantly on the lookout for opportunities to expand into other markets. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> succeeds primarily because of strong leadership, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Carey </PERSON>, a senior vice president with <ORGANIZATION> Airline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which publishes Airline Quarterly in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` They have proven to be able to make adjustments to their operating strategies as the marketplace requires,'' <PERSON> Carey </PERSON> said. `` I do like the fundamentals of the company,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Karos </PERSON>, a financial airline analyst for <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` They clearly are well into a turnaround.'' For its first five years, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> averaged about 65 percent annual growth in carrying capacity but lost money in all but one year, <PERSON> Karos </PERSON> said. In 1988, he said, the company began to slow its growth in seat-miles to focus on profitability. It posted a profit in the second quarter of 1988 and has been profitable each quarter since then. `` They changed their operating strategy,'' <PERSON> Carey </PERSON> said. `` They actually changed from their emphasis on long-haul operations and re-emphasized the feeder services through <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> and have improved their profitability because of that revenue growth.'' <PERSON> Carey </PERSON> said trans-Pacific air service is growing at a higher rate than travel to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and is almost triple domestic growth. <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> was serious about buying the shuttle but ran out of time to come up with the financing. The airline is going ahead with expansion of service to the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> through <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> LaGuardia </LOCATION> via landing slots acquired in May. America West needs approval from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> and the Japanese government before it can start service to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. Deregulation provided opportunity but also unprecedented competition, and most of the new entrants failed. `` There's not many survivors,'' <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said. He is one of them. The <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> native entered the industry in 1960 as an accountant for <ORGANIZATION> Frontier </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and moved through jobs in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. In 1981, while in <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> for a second time, he linked up with current company president <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Conway </PERSON>, who had quit as a vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. By 1983, <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON>, <PERSON> Conway </PERSON> and five others had raised $ 20 million through public stock offerings and bank financing and were ready to fly. The company started service Aug. 1 of that year with 280 employees and three <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s, serving four points between <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>.; today, <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> has 8,800 employees and serves 47 cities. <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said he chose the <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> area because no carrier dominated the region. `` Other airlines failed to see the opportunity,'' he said. `` The timing was right to build a hub-and-spoke system.'' Two constants of the airline's history have been its original marketing slogan _ `` Less Fare, <ORGANIZATION> More </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION>'' _ and management's willingness to bend over backward to keep its employees from union afflilation <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> offered `` more care'' through assigned seating, complimentary beverages and free copies of the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> and USA Today. After some complaints about late flights, the carrier recovered and ranks first in on-time operations for the period since the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> began keeping figures in 1987. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> employees are stockholders who participate in a profit-sharing program. Employees move around, working as a flight attendant one day and taking reservations or doing ramp duties the next. `` It's helped <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> be extremely productive and given individuals very good professional atmosphere,'' <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON> said. The practices apparently convinced employees to reject two unions in elections this year and keep their airline the nation's largest without any unionized employees. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> is largely non-unionized but has a weak flight attendants' union. <PERSON> Beauvais </PERSON>' second-floor office is directly beneath the flight paths into and out of <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, allowing the chief executive officer the opportunity to watch his planes land and take off. `` I do n't regret a moment of it,'' he said. `` I'd never work in any other industry.''
