<HEAD>May Department Stores Considers Sale of Discounters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 May <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Tuesday said it is exploring the possibility of selling its <ORGANIZATION> Caldor </ORGANIZATION> and Venture discount chains Divesting the two general merchandise discounters would enable the retailer to more easily pursue its intention to concentrate on its department store and shoe businesses. `` The divestiture of <ORGANIZATION> Caldor </ORGANIZATION> and Venture will allow May to focus on the operations and expansion of our higher-return and faster-growing businesses ...'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON>, May chairman and chief executive officer. May, one of the largest retailers in the country and owner of <ORGANIZATION> Lord </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hecht </PERSON>'s, <PERSON> Sibley </PERSON>'s, plus other department stores and specialty shoe chains, said it anticipates using a significant portion of the proceeds from a possible sale to buy back its stock. The remainder of any proceeds would be spent on general corporate purposes, including investment in the department store operations and shoe businesses, the company said in a news release. May management have been working to restore <ORGANIZATION> Caldor </ORGANIZATION> to higher levels of profitability and recently have expressed optimism about <ORGANIZATION> Caldor </ORGANIZATION>'s prospects. <ORGANIZATION> Caldor </ORGANIZATION>, which operates in the Northeast, was taken over by May in 1986 as part of the acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Goods </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Caldor </ORGANIZATION>'s operating earnings came to $ 50 million in 1988 on sales of $ 1.6 billion May launched Venture in 1970. It operates in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and last year had operating income of $ 81 million on sales of $ 1.3 billion. Both Venture and May sell a range of items including hard line goods, such as appliances, and soft line goods, such as clothing. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hays </PERSON>, May's president, described <ORGANIZATION> Caldor </ORGANIZATION> and Venture as two `` well-positioned businesses with excellent management and committed associates.'' As a condition of any sale, May will insist on provisions regarding jobs, compensation and benefits for <ORGANIZATION> Caldor </ORGANIZATION>'s and Venture's employees Retail industry analysts had been expecting that May eventually would shed <ORGANIZATION> Caldor </ORGANIZATION> and Venture. `` I think it was something we were all expecting them to do,'' said <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` But it is a little earlier than expected.'' <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON> said he thought May would have waited to look for buyers until <ORGANIZATION> Caldor </ORGANIZATION> and Venture had shown steady financial progress over a longer period of time. Given May's plan to use much of the money it would get from selling the two units to buy its shares, the move seems aimed chiefly at enhancing the value of the retailer's stock. Some shareholders had become disgruntled when May diluted its earnings through the acquisitions of the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Goods </ORGANIZATION> properties in 1986 and then the <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s and <ORGANIZATION> Filene </ORGANIZATION>'s department store chains in 1988. `` I think it's an attractive move for them to make as far as shareholders are concerned,'' said <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON> said May has asked the investment banking firm <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Inc. to look into the move With the addition of <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s and <PERSON> Filene </PERSON>'s last year, May's 14 department store divisions produced sales of $ 7.5 billion and operating earnings of $ 802 million. Volume Shoe's sales were $ 1.1 billion with operating earnings of $ 138 million. May, which is based in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, currently operates 283 department stores in 29 states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, 120 <ORGANIZATION> Caldor </ORGANIZATION> stores in eight states in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, 73 Venture stores in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> and 2,628 Volume Shoe stores in 43 states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>.
