<SECOND>BC-Kodak Worries, Adv 02,1039</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 2, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kodak Can't Find Formula For Success</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sustaining success has been difficult for <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> this decade and that's one reason the company's name keeps coming up on <LOCATION> Wall </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION> as a possible takeover target The company has managed to turn around a sagging bottom line twice since 1980, only to see the same problems _ increased competition, a rising <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar and higher costs _ return to chew up profits. `` It seems like they wipe their brow and say, ` Whew, we're glad that's over,' and they turn around and have to do it all over again,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Obenzinger </PERSON>, a stock analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Wood </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gundy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Call it the three-year twitch. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> laid off thousands of workers in 1983 saying unfavorable exchange rates and soft markets overseas had hurt its business. The company's profits went up 63 percent the next year. In 1986, the company had to lay off more than 10,000 workers, radically restructure the company and start a cost-cutting program in an effort to remain competitive. Profits more than tripled the next year and set a record in 1988. Now in 1989, after profits declined 23 percent in the first quarter of the year, the company has announced plans to cut costs by consolidating its photofinishing and consumer photography units, which could mean hundreds of layoffs. `` It does seem to go in cycles and we're at the point where the company is under pressure again,'' said <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Glazer </PERSON>, a stock analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> is having trouble controlling expenses at <ORGANIZATION> Sterling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which it bought for $ 5.1 billion last year. And the company is battling in court to prevent a large damage award to <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in the two companies' patent infringement lawsuit over instant photography. As if all these problems-that-won ` t-go-away are n't enough, <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> was named last month as the 1 emitter of the industrial pollutant methylene chloride by a Washington-based environmental group. Analysts point to several reasons for <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>'s roller-coaster ride through the'80s. First and foremost is the value of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar. When the dollar is strong compared to other countries' currencies, <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> gets hurt in two ways: its profits overseas are smaller when translated back into dollars, and foreign rivals gain a price advantage in sales to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market This double whammy hurt <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> throughout the first half of the decade and helped competitors like <ORGANIZATION> Fuji </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Photo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Agfa-Gevaert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> loosen <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>'s strangle hold on photographic film sales around the world. In the 1970s, <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> sold between 90 and 95 percent of all photographic film in the world. Today, that has fallen to between 80 and 85 percent, according to industry estimates. The dollar has been gaining strength for the past year and, unless it weakens soon, <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> is going to have to continue cutting costs to offset the losses it will bring. `` I'm not sounding alarm right now on the dollar, but I'm getting ready to,'' <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>'s Chairman <PERSON> Colby </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said. `` If it has n't started down by year-end, I'm going to be concerned. <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said it's difficult to determine how much of <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>'s woes can be traced to outside factors like the dollar or to management decisions made by <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> executives `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> basically has sort of a chip on its shoulder these days. We're always trying to find who's to blame for something,'' <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said. `` Instead of taking responsibility, we have learned to blame everyone else but ourselves for what goes wrong.'' He said he does n't want <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> to join that chorus. In an effort to become more in control, <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said the company is planning to sell a number of its businesses that have either been developed within the company or been acquired. `` Each one will not make a significant impact on the company or the public eye, they're not that big. But the idea is very powerful inside the company,'' <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> remains a benevolent corporate father figure to the <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION> area, where it remains the largest employer, said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Enderlin </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` Their idea of dramatic cost-cutting and dramatic restructuring really is n't that dramatic,'' <PERSON> Enderlin </PERSON> said. `` They still have a mentality that is somewhat paternalistic.'' Questions about <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> being too nice only pump up the takeover talk on Wall Street. Rumors have swirled in the past few weeks speculating that corporate raider <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Icahn </PERSON> has begun looking at the company and that <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> might be considering a merger with <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. With takeovers sweeping corporate <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, stock analysts are n't surprised that <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>'s name has popped up on the merger and acquisitions menu, but most agree a takeover of the company is `` These rumors get started because the company has characteristics that attract corporate raiders, but the odds are against a takeover attempt,'' said <PERSON> Glazer </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> is a well-known name, it's in a good industry and it's being managed for long-term growth, three things that appeal to corporate raiders who want companies that can be changed around to yield more money right away `` I guess there are some people who believe that some outside group can wave a magic wand and change <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> from an ugly duckling into a beautiful swan,'' said <PERSON> Enderlin </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's not that easy.'' <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION>'s businesses are complex. The company also has a number of hurdles that give it some protection from potential hostile takeovers. The company is incorporated in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, which has tough anti-takeover laws. If a raider acquired a majority of <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> stock, management could issue enough new stock to friendly buyers to outvote the raider. The company also has about $ 13 billion in long - and short-term debt, which would increase the cost of a leveraged buyout `` Nothing's impossible, but a takeover attempt would be hard to believe,'' said <PERSON> Obenzinger </PERSON>.
