<FIRST>r f AM-S&amp;Ls-Wall     06-27 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;Ls-Wall,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wall Sees More Initial Spending If Congress Restricts New Agency's
Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration will be forced to double its initial spending on savings and loan rescues if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> restricts the financial power of the new <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L bailout agency, thrift regulator <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> said Tuesday. If a congressional conference committee next month adopts the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> version of the S & amp; L bill, <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> said the new agency, called the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, would need to spend at least twice the $ 50 billion it is due to receive over the next three years. The House bill, unlike the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> version, forbids the bailout agency from issuing promissory notes or loss guarantees extending its liability beyond the $ 50 billion. Wall, speaking at a conference of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> of Saving Institutions, the industry's largest trade group, said $ 50 billion represents the net cost of closing and merging insolvent thrifts. It reflects the cost after the government recovers some of its expenses by selling real estate inherited from failed S & amp; Ls, he said. Unless the agency can rescue institutions by issuing promissory notes and paying them off years later after the government sells the real estate, the initial cash outlay needed will be at least $ 100 billion, he said. In that case, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would be forced to ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in several years for more money. Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, insisted on the restriction, arguing that Wall's agency, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, abused its note-writing powers last year and, in effect, spent money without congressional approval. He has said he wants to ensure the <ORGANIZATION> Resolution </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which will take over some of the bank board's duties, will not have similar leeway. Wall also complained about another provision in the House bill that makes the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> the primary regulator of state-chartered S & amp; Ls, taking away that power from the agency that will succeed the bank board. Wall's agency, under the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> version, retains its power over both state and federal S & amp; Ls. <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> said that would create conflicts of interest in the future because the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION>, as the insuror of S & amp; L deposits, likely will become part-owner of rescued institutions. The <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> should not regulate institutions it owns while at the same time regulating privately owned competing institutions, he said. On another topic, <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> said both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L bills do not give his agency and the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> enough power to allow capital-deficient savings and loans to continue operating. <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> said that even advocates of very tough capital rules believe regulators ought to have the leeway to allow undercapitalized <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls to continue operating provided they are profitable, have competent managers and stick to a plan to increase their capital. However, a recent review by bank board lawyers indicates that regulators do not have enough authority to grant that leeway. `` There's too much pressure to say no and not enough ability to say yes,'' he said.
</TEXT>
