<HEAD>Wheat Futures Surge With Hopes For Soviet Buying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Wheat futures prices bounded to a six-week high Tuesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> in anticipation of further buying of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which apparently is strapped for supplies. On other markets, livestock and meat futures were mostly lower while oil and precious-metals futures were mixed. Wheat settled -LCB- cent to 10 -RCB- cents higher with the contract for delivery in July at $ 4.12 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 3 -RCB- cents to 5 cents higher with July at $ 2.62 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 4 -RCB- cents to 5 -LCB- cents higher with July at $ 1.53 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 8 cents to 13 cents higher with July at $ 7.38 -LCB- a bushel. The rally pushed wheat futures to their highest level since May 15 and erased most of Monday's steep losses in the corn, soybean and oat markets. Unlike the other grain markets, wheat futures had risen Monday on rumors the Soviets had bought up to 500,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat at market prices, an indication they had an immediate need for the grain. Most of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s recent purchases of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grain have been through the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Export Enhancement Program, which effectively subsidizes grain sales and requires buyers to submit bids in a process that is not always speedy. After the close of trading Tuesday, the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> said private exporters had reported sales of 400,000 metric tons of soft red winter wheat to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for delivery during the current marketing year, which began Oct. 1. Tuesday's rally was fueled by speculation that the Soviets would be back for more wheat and by reports of rain-induced harvest delays in the central and southern states where soft red winter wheat is grown. `` There are also a lot of quality concerns about the soft red wheat, which makes large-scale buying particularly bullish,'' said <PERSON> Katharina </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmer </PERSON>, a grain-market analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Markets </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, reversing Monday's trend. The hog market led the way down, reflecting lower spot hog prices and perceptions that the market was nearing a top. Cattle futures were pressured by slack demand and ample supplies. Live cattle settled .35 cent lower to .07 cent higher with August at 70.57 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .27 cent lower with August at 81.25 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent to .87 cent lower with July at 49.10 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .80 cent lower to .50 cent higher with July at 34.75 cents a pound. Heating-oil and crude-oil futures rose for the fifth straight day on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> but the gasoline market's rally ended with a modest decline. Analysts said the market's uncertain performance indicated that a downturn _ a so-called technical correction _ was likely. West Texas Intermediate crude settled 6 cents to 23 cents higher with August at $ 20.48 a barrel; heating oil was .35 cent to .88 cent higher with July at 50.53 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .01 cent to .25 cent lower with July at 63.68 cents a gallon. Gold futures rose slightly while silver futures were nearly unchanged on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, in quiet trading that reflected the dollar's mixed performance against other major currencies. Gold settled $ 1.50 higher across the board with August at $ 379.80 a troy ounce; silver was unchanged to 1 cent lower with July at $ 5.31 a troy ounce.
