<HEAD>Stock Exchange Says Drexel Sanctions Decision Will Come After Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> is indicating the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> will take disciplinary measures against <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for the firm's involvement in Wall Street corruption. However, an <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said Tuesday the exchange would wait for <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> to settle the sweeping criminal securities fraud case brought against it by the federal government before deciding what sanctions if any to impose on the investment firm. <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> agreed to plead guilty to six felonies and pay $ 650 million in penalties to settle its criminal case, which involved alleged securities law violations stemming from the insider trading scandals linked to now-jailed speculator <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said in an interview with the Wall Street Journal that the settlement represents `` the biggest failure of the -LRB- supervisory -RRB- system in the history of the financial markets.'' <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> did not specify what sanctions were being considered, but the exchange could fine, censure or suspend the firm and employees. Issues before the exchange include whether top <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> officials failed to supervise employees properly. `` The last thing we want to do is come out looking like a wimp,'' <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> made comments last week that raised doubts about whether the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> would follow up on the federal sanctions being levied against <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` I'm not sure what purpose we would serve by adding any more to that since the commission could have done everything including bar -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- as a broker-dealer,'' he told a group of reporters. Exchange officials maintain <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> was not indicating the exchange would not take action against <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION>. `` We have not yet determined what action if any the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> will take in the <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> case,'' spokesman <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> <PERSON> Torrenzano </PERSON> said. `` That determination will be made in the coming weeks and months once federal regulators have completed all of their deliberations and settlements.'' A federal judge last week approved a civil settlement between the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> and the firm that places <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> under strict supervision for three years. Approval of the separate criminal settlement is pending before another judge. Once that happens, <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> said, `` we will go full blast.'' `` The exchange has been talking to the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> and has been examining the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>'s proposed settlement,'' <PERSON> Torrenzano </PERSON> said. In 1985, the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> fined <ORGANIZATION> E.F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> $ 400,000 and censured its president and chief financial officer for failing to supervise the firm properly after <PERSON> Hutton </PERSON> pleaded guilty to federal mail and wire fraud charges in a wide-ranging check-kiting scheme.
