<HEAD>Oil Higher; Gasoline Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crude oil and wholesale heating oil futures continued to climb Tuesday, carried aloft largely by technical buying. Gasoline futures prices pulled back. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the August contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> rose 23 cents to $ 20.48 per 42-gallon barrel. The contract closed with a gain of 54 cents on Monday. Contracts for later delivery of WTI, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, posted similar increases. Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the July contract for No. 2 heating oil gained 0.88 cent to settle at 50.53 cents a gallon, adding to Monday's gain of 0.16 cent Other contract months of heating oil also finished higher. The contact for July delivery of unleaded gasoline edged down by 0.01 cent to 63.68 a gallon after Monday's surge of 0.77 cent. Contracts for August, September and October gasoline delivery also declined. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Haskins </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said the rally in the crude futures pits was sustained with the help of technical buying. Buying bred more buying as traders pushed the price of crude futures past thresholds considered significant. `` The technicals have pointed upward now for a week and a half and until we get some dramatic bearish news the market will keep moving higher,'' said <PERSON> Haskins </PERSON>. `` The market looks like it wants to head to $ 21 or $ 21.20 -LRB- a barrel -RRB- in the near term.'' The market also has been getting a lift this week from news that some <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members intend to curb crude production. Published reports have said <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION>, two chronic overproducers, will reduce their output levels closer to the amount desired by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> previously had rejected its OPEC-imposed production ceiling and set its own quota. Both <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> UAE </ORGANIZATION> reportedly now plan to scale back production levels but keep them above the amount mandated by the oil cartel at a meeting in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, earlier this month.
