<HEAD>Time-Paramount Struggle Could Affect Future of Friendly Mergers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Now that <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has rejected a sweetened $ 12.2 billion takeover bid from <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the focus of their struggle is shifting to <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, not only the fate of <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> but also the future of friendly mergers may be decided in court. Time is fighting to preserve a planned merger with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> _ and it is that merger on which the takeover fight may turn. Paramount, after announcing its original $ 175-a-share, or $ 10.7 billion, bid on June 6, filed suit in <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> to stop the transaction that would create <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest communications concern All three companies are incorporated in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>. Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> first proposed their friendly stock-for-stock merger transaction in March. After Paramount began its pursuit of Time, the merger agreement was amended and <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> began a $ 14 billion tender offer for its would-be partner. Paramount contends Time opened up a <ORGANIZATION> Pandora </ORGANIZATION>'s box _ effectively putting itself up for sale _ by announcing it would merge with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>. Under <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> law, if a company has put itself up for sale, its board is required to seek the maximum value for shareholders. If the court rules that <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> in fact put itself up for sale, the company's board could be hard-pressed to reject <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 200-a-share bid, which is $ 74 higher than the price at which Time stock traded before Paramount announced its bid Time rejected Paramount's latest offer Monday, calling it financially inadequate and subject to too many conditions. Time contends that its merger plans with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> did not put the company up for sale, meaning its board does not have to consider higher bids. A court hearing on the issue is scheduled for July 11. The case has generating much interest among companies and corporate lawyers because of the possibility it could set a precedent affecting mergers between other companies. Many <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies _ including about half of the Fortune 500 _ are incorporated in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> to take advantage of state tax laws aimed at attracting business. As a result, business law decisions by the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> courts _ which have established a strong reputation in dealing with corporate issues _ widely are seen as important precedents. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> DeAngelo </PERSON>, a professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION>, said a ruling in <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s favor could place a chill on friendly mergers such as the original <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> deal in favor of cash buyouts. `` You would want to make sure, if you did n't want to be acquired, you were clearly the buyer'' in a deal, he said. But <PERSON> DeAngelo </PERSON> said a ruling favoring <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> would not necessarily mean an end to mergers such as the <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> deal, and predicted that corporate lawyers would find a way to structure mergers in accordance with such a ruling. `` You'll see a period of uncertainty and people will tread carefully as they get used to the new rules,'' he said. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Margotta </PERSON>, a professor at <ORGANIZATION> Northeastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, said that even if the court rules in <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s favor, a merger transaction structured differently from the <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> proposal might not be affected. However, <PERSON> Margotta </PERSON> said, a ruling against <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> is `` going to make it much more difficult'' to accomplish a friendly stock-swap merger. Many observers decline to predict how the court might rule, but some believe the fight will come down to a question of money and <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 200-a-share bid. `` The legal issue is nothing more than a subterfuge for some basic economic conflicts,'' said <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Rappaport </PERSON>, a professor at <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kellogg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Graduate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>. Time stock has fluctuated since Paramount announced its bid, as traders try to forecast how the court might rule and how the struggle will end. On Tuesday, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> stock slipped 75 cents to $ 163.25 a share in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> composite trading. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> was up 25 cents to $ 59.12 -LCB- a share, and Paramount was down 87 -LCB- cents to $ 60.37 -LCB- a share.
</TEXT>
